# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crispr-gene-editing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The Cas9 endonuclease introduces site-specific double-stranded breaks in DNA, enabling gene inactivation, removal, or insertion through cellular repair mechanisms such as non-homologous end joining or homologous recombination.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 was discovered in *S. pyogenes* and later in *S. thermophilus.* It functions with two small RNAs—crRNA and tracrRNA—to form a four-component complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2012, Doudna and Charpentier fused the RNAs into a single-guide RNA, enabling Cas9 to cut specific DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These developments spurred genome modification efforts, including groups led by Zhang and Church who showed genome editing in human cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Variants of Cas9, including Cas9 nickase (Cas9n), that create single-strand breaks, and versions recognizing different PAM sequences, address specific Cas9 limitations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR-Cas9 technology has raised ethical and regulatory concerns, particularly regarding human germline editing and genetic enhancement.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The CRISPR/Cas system evolved in nature as a means for bacteria to protect themselves from invading viruses and bacteriophages by inserting pieces of their DNA into the host genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This allowed the adaptive immune system to respond accordingly on a subsequent infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] It was discovered in *Streptococcus pyogenes* and later found across many other species.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 was first identified in *Streptococcus pyogenes* as a CRISPR-associated protein, originally referred to as Cas5, involved in the bacterial adaptive immune system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Studies found Cas9 contains a nuclease domain, the effector enzyme responsible for generating double-stranded DNA breaks in the type II CRISPR system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Researchers identified that Cas9 activity depends on two RNA molecules: CRISPR RNA (crRNA), which guides the enzyme to target DNA sequences, and trans-activating CRISPR RNA (tracrRNA), which is required for nuclease activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2012, Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier re-engineered the Cas9 endonuclease into a simplified two-component system by fusing the two RNA molecules into a single-guide RNA that, when combined with Cas9, could find and cut the DNA target specified by the guide RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] That same year, research showed that CRISPR Cas9 components could be programmed for site-specific double stranded DNA breaks in vitro, laying the foundation for genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] By manipulating the nucleotide sequence of the guide RNA, the artificial Cas9 system could be programmed to target and cleave DNA sequence for separation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Around the same time, a collaboration including Virginijus Šikšnys, Gasiūnas, Barrangou, and Horvath showed that Cas9 from the *S. thermophilus* CRISPR system can also be reprogrammed by modifying its crRNA sequence to target specific DNA sites.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2013, research groups led by Feng Zhang and George Church reported successful targeted DNA editing in human genomes, marking the first use of CRISPR-Cas9 for targeted modification in eukaryotic systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These findings advanced the development of CRISPR-Cas9 as a versatile genome editing tool across a wide range of organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Beyond DNA cleavage, CRISPR Cas9 has been modified to function as programmable transcription factors that allow activation or silencing of targeted genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The significance of the system's development was formally recognized in 2020, when Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna were awarded a Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their work in CRISPR Cas9 genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Native Cas9 is a 160-kilodalton endonuclease that requires a guide RNA composed of two distinct RNA molecules: CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2013, Mali, et al. and Gilbert, et al. reported that non-cleaving Cas9 variants can control transcriptional activators or repressors at specific DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In the same year, Bikard, et al. reported that dCas9 can block RNA polymerase at promoters or during elongation, silencing genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2014, Esvelt, Smidler, Catteruccia, and Church suggested that Cas9-based gene drives could spread genetic modifications through entire organism populations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2017, Li, et al. reported that Cas9 can target the end of the Hepatitis B viral genome ends, reducing infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Jensen et al., reported that dCas9 alters chromatin structure when fused to chromatin remodelers, .
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] O’Geen, et al., reported that dCas9 with FOG1 represses genes by methylating H3K27.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Lowder, et al., reported that dCas9 represses plant genes like *AtCSTF64* when fused to repressor domains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2018, Lee, et al., reported that engineered Cas9 reduces off-target effects by altering reaction rates.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2019, Chen and Page-McCaw reported that Cas9 suppresses HIV-1 long terminal repeats, mutating the viral genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2020, Uddin, Rudin, and Sen reported that Cas9 variants, such as Cas9 nickase, improve genome editing by reducing off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2025, Zhou, Diao, Li, and colleagues reported that **apoNmeCas9** (an RNA-free form of NmeCas9) can stimulate Cas1–Cas2-mediated CRISPR spacer acquisition in a type II-C system when CRISPR RNA levels are low.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR systems in bacteria and archaea function as programmable restriction enzymes to combat viruses and plasmids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR loci consist of short, palindromic repeats and variable spacers (24–48 nucleotides) that store sequences from foreign DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Adjacent cas genes, including universal cas1 and cas2, and type II-specific cas9, encode proteins for immunity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 uses crRNA and tracrRNA to form a complex that targets and cleaves foreign DNA matching the spacer sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] During the adaptation stage, CRISPR systems integrate spacers from viral"protospacers” into the CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] It requiring the presence of a PAM, such as NGG in *S.pyogenes*) for recognition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 ensures functional spacer acquisition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] However, spacers can be lost via homologous recombination.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The nuclease lobe alone is sufficient to stimulate acquisition, whereas crRNA-dependent regulation required full-length Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This activity is evolutionarily conserved across several type II-C Cas9 orthologues.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] RNA polymerase transcribes the CRISPR locus into pre-crRNA, which is processed by specific endoribonucleases into mature crRNAs, each containing one spacer and a partial repeat.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In the interference stage, the crRNA guides Cas9 together with tracrRNA to complementary foreing DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] If the targer sequence matches the spacer and a PAM is present, Cas9 introduces double-stranded breaks in DNA, stoping viral replication.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Inactive Cas9 (dCas9), lacking endonuclease activity, can bind DNA and regulate transcription.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In eukaryotic cells, dCas9 targets enhancer sequences to prevent transcription factor binding and gene expression.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Genome-wide screens using dCas9-based repression have been conducted to systematically identify gene funciton.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In addition to DNA targeting, Cas9 has been shown to cleave mRNA when hybridized with complementary single-stranded containing a PAM complement.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] When fused to transcription activators, dCas9 can be used to activate genes(CRISPRa).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has a bi-lobed structure with an alpha-helical lobe (REC) and a nuclease lobe (NUC) containing HNH and RuvC domains, connected by a bridge helix.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The nuclease lobe contains HNH domains which cleaves target DNA strands, and RuvC which cleaves the non-target strand.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The PAM-interacting domain recognizes the NGG PAM sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The single-guide RNA (sgRNA), replaces the crRNA-tracrRNA complex, and forms a T-shaped structure with the target DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] A 2014 study reported that REC1 and bridge helix domains are critical for sgRNA recognition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Bacterial restriction-modification systems can degrade foreign DNA introduced into the cell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These systems recognize specific DNA sequences and cleave foreign DNA, including Cas9-introduced genes, hindering genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR/Cas9 can help with bacterial defense against invaders such as bacteriophages, plasmids, and DNA viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9, guided by RNA, acts as an endonuclease enzyme, targeting and cleaving foreign DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] It unwinds foreign DNA and cleaves matching sites, similar to the RNA interference mechanism in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Other versions of Cas9 can bind but not cleave DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] They can be used to control transcriptional activator or repressor genes and manage gene activation and repression.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] More technically, Cas9 is a RNA-guided DNA endonuclease enzyme associated with the Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats (CRISPR) adaptive immune system in *Streptococcus pyogenes*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] *S. pyogenes* utilizes CRISPR to memorize and Cas9 to later interrogate and cleave foreign DNA, such as invading bacteriophage DNA or plasmid DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 performs this interrogation by unwinding foreign DNA and checking for sites complementary to the 20 nucleotide spacer region of the guide RNA (gRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] If the DNA substrate is complementary to the guide RNA, Cas9 cleaves the invading DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In this sense, the CRISPR-Cas9 mechanism parallels the RNA interference (RNAi) mechanism in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Apart from its original function in bacterial immunity, Cas9 has been utilized as a genome engineering tool to induce site-directed double-strand breaks in DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These breaks can lead to gene inactivation or the introduction of heterologous genes through non-homologous end joining and homologous recombination respectively in model organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Research on cas9 variants has been a promising way of overcoming the limitation of the CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Examples include Cas9 nickase (Cas9n), a variant that induces single-stranded breaks (SSBs) or variants recognizing different PAM sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Alongside zinc finger nucleases and transcription activator-like effector nuclease (TALEN) proteins, Cas9 is becoming a prominent tool in the field of genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has gained traction in recent years because it can cleave nearly any sequence complementary to the guide RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Because the target specificity of Cas9 stems from the guide RNA:DNA complementarity and not modifications to the protein itself (like TALENs and zinc fingers), engineering Cas9 to target new DNA is straightforward.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 targeting has been simplified through the engineering of a chimeric single guide RNA (chiRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Scientists have suggested that Cas9-based gene drives may be capable of editing the genomes of entire populations of organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2015, Cas9 was used to modify the genome of human embryos for the first time.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] To survive in a variety of challenging, inhospitable habitats that are filled with bacteriophages, bacteria and archaea have evolved methods to evade and fend off predatory viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This includes the CRISPR system of adaptive immunity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In practice, CRISPR/Cas systems act as self-programmable restriction enzymes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR loci are composed of short, palindromic repeats that occur at regular intervals composed of alternate CRISPR repeats and variable CRISPR spacers between 24 and 48 nucleotides long.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These CRISPR loci are usually accompanied by adjacent CRISPR-associated (cas) genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2005, it was discovered by three separate groups that the spacer regions were homologous to foreign DNA elements, including plasmids and viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These reports provided the first biological evidence that CRISPRs might function as an immune system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has been used often as a genome-editing tool.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has been used in recent developments in preventing viruses from manipulating hosts' DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Since the CRISPR-Cas9 was developed from bacterial genome systems, it can be used to target the genetic material in viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The use of the enzyme Cas9 can be a solution to many viral infections.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 possesses the ability to target specific viruses by the targeting of specific strands of the viral genetic information.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] More specifically the Cas9 enzyme targets certain sections of the viral genome that prevents the virus from carrying out its normal function.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has also been used to disrupt the detrimental strand of DNA and RNA that cause diseases and mutated strands of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has already showed promise in disrupting the effects of HIV-1.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has been shown to suppress the expression of the long terminal repeats in HIV-1.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] When introduced into the HIV-1 genome Cas9 has shown the ability to mutate strands of HIV-1.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has also been used in the treatment of Hepatitis B through targeting of the ends of certain of long terminal repeats in the Hepatitis B viral genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 has been used to repair the mutations causing cataracts in mice.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR-Cas systems are divided into three major types (type I, type II, and type III) and twelve subtypes, which are based on their genetic content and structural differences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] However, the core defining features of all CRISPR-Cas systems are the cas genes and their proteins: cas1 and cas2 are universal across types and subtypes, while cas3, cas9, and cas10 are signature genes for type I, type II, and type III, respectively.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Adaptation involves recognition and integration of spacers between two adjacent repeats in the CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The "Protospacer" refers to the sequence on the viral genome that corresponds to the spacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] A short stretch of conserved nucleotides exists proximal to the protospacer, which is called the protospacer adjacent motif (PAM).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The PAM is a recognition motif that is used to acquire the DNA fragment.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In type II, Cas9 recognizes the PAM during adaptation in order to ensure the acquisition of functional spacers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Loss of spacers and even groups of several have also been observed by Aranaz et al.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This probably occurs through homologous recombination of the between-repeat material.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] CRISPR expression includes the transcription of a primary transcript called a CRISPR RNA (pre-crRNA), which is transcribed from the CRISPR locus by RNA polymerase.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Specific endoribonucleases then cleave the pre-crRNAs into small CRISPR RNAs (crRNAs).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Interference involves the crRNAs within a multi-protein complex called CASCADE, which can recognize and specifically base-pair with regions of inserting complementary foreign DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The crRNA-foreign nucleic acid complex is then cleaved, however if there are mismatches between the spacer and the target DNA, or if there are mutations in the PAM, then cleavage will not be initiated.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In the latter scenario, the foreign DNA is not targeted for attack by the cell, thus the replication of the virus proceeds and the host is not immune to viral infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The interference stage can be mechanistically and temporally distinct from CRISPR acquisition and expression, yet for complete function as a defense system, all three phases must be functional.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Protospacers and protospacer-associated motifs (shown in red) are acquired at the "leader" end of a CRISPR array in the host DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The CRISPR array is composed of spacer sequences (shown in colored boxes) flanked by repeats (black diamonds).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This process requires Cas1 and Cas2 (and Cas9 in type II), which are encoded in the cas locus, which are usually located near the CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Pre-crRNA is transcribed starting at the leader region by the host RNA polymerase and then cleaved by Cas proteins into smaller crRNAs containing a single spacer and a partial repeat (shown as hairpin structure with colored spacers).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Stage 3: CRISPR interference. crRNA with a spacer that has strong complementarity to the incoming foreign DNA begins a cleavage event (depicted with scissors), which requires Cas proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] DNA cleavage interferes with viral replication and provides immunity to the host.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The interference stage can be functionally and temporarily distinct from CRISPR acquisition and expression (depicted by white line dividing the cell).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] dCas9, also referred to as endonuclease deficient Cas9 can be utilized to edit gene expression when applied to the transcription binding site of the desired section of a gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The optimal function of dCas9 is attributed to its mode of action.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Gene expression is inhibited when nucleotides are no longer added to the RNA chain and therefore terminating elongation of that chain, and as a result affects the transcription process.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This process occurs when dCas9 is mass-produced so it is able to affect the most genes at any given time via a sequence specific guide RNA molecule.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Since dCas9 appears to down regulate gene expression, this action is amplified even more when it is used in conjunction with repressive chromatin modifier domains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The dCas9 protein has other functions outside of the regulation of gene expression.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] A promoter can be added to the dCas9 protein which allows them to work with each other to become efficient at beginning or stopping transcription at different sequences along a strand of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These two proteins are specific in where they act on a gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This is prevalent in certain types of prokaryotes when a promoter and dCas9 align themselves together to impede the ability of elongation of polymer of nucleotides coming together to form a transcribed piece of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Without the promoter, the dCas9 protein does not have the same effect by itself or with a gene body.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] When examining the effects of repression of transcription further, H3K27, an amino acid component of a histone, becomes methylated through the interaction of dCas9 and a peptide called FOG1.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Essentially, this interaction causes gene repression on the C + N terminal section of the amino acid complex at the specific junction of the gene, and as a result, terminates transcription.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] dCas9 also proves to be efficient when it comes to altering certain proteins that can create diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] When the dCas9 attaches to a form of RNA called guide-RNA, it prevents the proliferation of repeating codons and DNA sequences that might be harmful to an organism's genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Further explanation of how the dCas9 protein works can be found in their utilization of plant genomes by the regulation of gene production in plants to either increase or decrease certain characteristics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The CRISPR-CAS9 system has the ability to either upregulate or downregulate genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The dCas9 proteins are a component of the CRISPR-CAS9 system and these proteins can repress certain areas of a plant gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This happens when dCAS9 binds to repressor domains, and in the case of the plants, deactivation of a regulatory gene such as AtCSTF64, does occur.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Bacteria are another focus of the usage of dCas9 proteins as well.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Since eukaryotes have a larger DNA makeup and genome; the much smaller bacteria are easy to manipulate.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] As a result, eukaryotes use dCas9 to inhibit RNA polymerase from continuing the process of transcription of genetic material.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 features a bi-lobed architecture with the guide RNA nestled between the alpha-helical lobe (blue) and the nuclease lobe (cyan, orange, and gray).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These two lobes are connected through a single bridge helix.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] There are two nuclease domains located in the multi-domain nuclease lobe, the RuvC (gray) which cleaves the non-target DNA strand, and the HNH nuclease domain (cyan) that cleaves the target strand of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The RuvC domain is encoded by sequentially disparate sites that interact in the tertiary structure to form the RuvC cleavage domain (See right figure).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] A key feature of the target DNA is that it must contain a protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) consisting of the three-nucleotide sequence- NGG.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This PAM is recognized by the PAM-interacting domain (PI domain, orange) located near the C-terminal end of Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 undergoes distinct conformational changes between the apo (apoenzyme), guide RNA bound, and guide RNA:DNA bound states.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 recognizes the stem-loop architecture inherent in the CRISPR locus, which mediates the maturation of crRNA-tracrRNA ribonucleoprotein complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 in complex with CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA) further recognizes and degrades the target dsDNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In the co-crystal structure shown here, the crRNA-tracrRNA complex is replaced by a chimeric single-guide RNA (sgRNA, in red) which has been proved to have the same function as the natural RNA complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The sgRNA base paired with target ssDNA is anchored by Cas9 as a T-shaped architecture.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This crystal structure of the DNA-bound Cas9 enzyme reveals distinct conformational changes in the alpha-helical lobe with respect to the nuclease lobe, as well as the location of the HNH domain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The protein consists of a recognition lobe (REC) and a nuclease lobe (NUC).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] All regions except the HNH form tight interactions with each other and sgRNA-ssDNA complex, while the HNH domain forms few contacts with the rest of the protein.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In another conformation of Cas9 complex observed in the crystal, the HNH domain is not visible.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These structures suggest the conformational flexibility of HNH domain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] To date, at least three crystal structures have been studied and published.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] One representing a conformation of Cas9 in the apo state, and two representing Cas9 in the DNA bound state.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In sgRNA-Cas9 complex, based on the crystal structure, REC1, BH and PI domains have important contacts with backbone or bases in both repeat and spacer region.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Several Cas9 mutants including REC1 or REC2 domains deletion and residues mutations in BH have been tested.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] REC1 and BH related mutants show lower or none activity compared with wild type, which indicate these two domains are crucial for the sgRNA recognition at repeat sequence and stabilization of the whole complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Although the interactions between spacer sequence and Cas9 as well as PI domain and repeat region need further studies, the co-crystal demonstrates clear interface between Cas9 and sgRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cas9 contains two nuclease domains an McrA-like HNH nuclease domain and a RuvC-like nuclease domain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These HNH domain cleaves the complementary (target) DNA strand, while the RuvC-like nuclease domains are responsible for cleavage of the non-complementary (non-target DNA strands).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Despite low sequence similarity, the region homologous to RNase H adopts a RuvC fold and the HNH region folds similarly to T4 Endo VII, a member of the HNH endonuclease family.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Wild-type *Streptococcus pyogenes* Cas9 requires magnesium (Mg2+) cofactors for RNA-mediated DNA cleavage, although varying levels of activity has been observed in the presence of other divalent metal ions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] For example, in the presence of manganese (Mn2+), Cas9 has been shown to be exhibit RNA-independent DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] DNA cleavage requires the presence of a protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) located at the non-target strand three nucleotides downstream from the cleavage site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Pyogenes* Cas9 is NGG, but alternative motifs like NAG and NGA are tolerated with lower cleavage activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] relatively rapid (*k* ≥ 700 s−1), the release of the cleavage products is very slow (*t*1/2 = ln(2)/*k* ≈ 43–91 h), essentially rendering Cas9 a single-turnover enzyme.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Additional studies regarding the kinetics of Cas9 have shown engineered Cas9 to be effective in reducing off-target effects by modifying the rate of the reaction.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Cleavage efficiency depends on several factors, including PAM recognition, nucleotide composition of the 20 nucleotide spacer-complementary region of the gRNAm.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The most relevant nucleotide composition properties that impact efficiency are those in the PAM-proximal region.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Free energy changes of nucleic acids are also highly relevant in defining cleavage activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Guide RNAs that bind to the DNA forming a duplex that falls into a restricted range of binding free energy changes that excludes extremely weak or stable bindings generally perform efficiently.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Stable guide RNA folding conformations can also impair cleavage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The seminal structural characterization of the nuclease demonstrated that the HNH domain precisely cleaves between the positions 18 and 17 (18|17) of the protospacer, while the RuvC cleaves the non-target strand at corresponding and downstream positions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Molecular dynamics simulations reported that cleavage of the NTS between 17|16 of the target sequence was more energetically favored than 18|17, generating 1 nucleotide 5' ssDNA overhangs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Notably, the authors demonstrated that the 5' overhangs are filled in during DNA repair, resulting in templated insertions, where the 5' overhang is used as a template by Pol4 for the repair reaction.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The association between staggered cleavage and precise templated insertions have been supported by additional studies in human cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The nucleotide composition of the five bases closest to the PAM in the target sequence also affects the scission profile, influencing whether DNA cleavage is blunt or staggered.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In 2024 a high-throughput investigation of Cas9 scission profile revealed that ~85% of on-target cleavage is blunt, whereas ~15% had a 1 nucleotide 5' overhang.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Off-targets had a higher staggered cleavage rate compared to on-target sites, with approximately 1/3 of off-targets displaying 5' overhangs from 1 to 3 nucleotides.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Sequence patterns within the target region were shown to favor the formation of either blunt or staggered DNA cuts, and staggered cleavage was associated with the formation of predictable insertion-deletion (indel) outcomes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Most archaea and bacteria stubbornly refuse to allow a Cas9 to edit their genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This is because they can attach foreign DNA, that does not affect them, into their genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Another way that these cells defy Cas9 is by process of restriction modification (RM) system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] When a bacteriophage enters a bacteria or archaea cell it is targeted by the RM system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The RM system then cuts the bacteriophages DNA into separate pieces by restriction enzymes and uses endonucleases to further destroy the strands of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This poses a problem to Cas9 editing because the RM system also targets the foreign genes added by the Cas9 process.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Due to the unique ability of Cas9 to bind to essentially any complement sequence in any genome, researchers wanted to use this enzyme to repress transcription of various genomic loci.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] To accomplish this, the two crucial catalytic residues of the RuvC and HNH domain can be mutated to alanine abolishing all endonuclease activity of Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] The resulting protein coined 'dead' Cas9 or 'dCas9' for short, can still tightly bind to dsDNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This catalytically inactive Cas9 variant has been used for both mechanistic studies into Cas9 DNA interrogative binding and as a general programmable DNA binding RNA-Protein complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Also, dCas9 can be targeted to the coding region of loci such that inhibition of RNA Polymerase occurs during the elongation phase of transcription.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In Eukaryotes, silencing of gene expression can be extended by targeting dCas9 to enhancer sequences, where dCas9 can block assembly of transcription factors leading to silencing of specific gene expression.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This technology is similar in principle to RNAi such that gene expression is being modulated at the RNA level.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] However, the dCas9 approach has gained much traction as there exist less off-target effects and in general larger and more reproducible silencing effects through the use of dCas9 compared to RNAi screens.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Furthermore, because the dCas9 approach to gene silencing can be quantitatively controlled, a researcher can now precisely control the extent to which a gene of interest is repressed allowing more questions about gene regulation and gene stoichiometry to be answered.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Beyond direct binding of dCas9 to transcriptionally sensitive positions of loci, dCas9 can be fused to a variety of modulatory protein domains to carry out a myriad of functions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Recently, dCas9 has been fused to chromatin remodeling proteins (HDACs/HATs) to reorganize the chromatin structure around various loci.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This is important in targeting various eukaryotic genes of interest as heterochromatin structures hinder Cas9 binding.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Furthermore, because Cas9 can react to heterochromatin, it is theorized that this enzyme can be further applied to studying the chromatin structure of various loci.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Additionally, dCas9 has been employed in genome wide screens of gene repression.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] By employing large libraries of guide RNAs capable of targeting thousands of genes, genome wide genetic screens using dCas9 have been conducted.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Another method for silencing transcription with Cas9 is to directly cleave mRNA products with the catalytically active Cas9 enzyme.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This approach is made possible by hybridizing ssDNA with a PAM complement sequence to ssRNA allowing for a dsDNA-RNA PAM site for Cas9 binding.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] This technology makes available the ability to isolate endogenous RNA transcripts in cells without the need to induce chemical modifications to RNA or RNA tagging methods.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] In contrast to silencing genes, dCas9 can also be used to activate genes when fused to transcription activating factors.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] These factors include subunits of bacterial RNA Polymerase II and traditional transcription factors in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/cas9] Recently, genome-wide screens of transcription activation have also been accomplished using dCas9 fusions named 'CRISPRa' for activation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The technique is considered highly significant in biotechnology and medicine as it enables *in vivo* genome editing and is considered exceptionally precise, cost-effective, and efficient.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It can be used in the creation of new medicines, agricultural products, and genetically modified organisms, or as a means of controlling pathogens and pests.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It also offers potential in the treatment of inherited genetic diseases as well as diseases arising from somatic mutations, such as cancer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] However, its use in human germline genetic modification is highly controversial.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The development of this technique earned Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2020.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The third researcher group that shared the Kavli Prize for the same discovery, led by Virginijus Šikšnys, was not awarded the Nobel Prize.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Working like genetic scissors, the Cas9 nuclease opens both strands of the targeted DNA sequence to introduce the modification by one of two methods.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Knock-in mutations, facilitated via homology-directed repair (HDR), are the traditional pathway of targeted genomic editing approaches.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This allows for the introduction of targeted DNA damage and repair.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] HDR employs the use of similar DNA sequences to drive the repair of the break via the incorporation of exogenous DNA to function as the repair template.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This method relies on the periodic and isolated occurrence of DNA damage at the target site in order for the repair to commence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Knock-out mutations caused by CRISPR-Cas9 result from the repair of the double-stranded break by means of non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) or POLQ/polymerase theta-mediated end-joining (TMEJ).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] These end-joining pathways can often result in random deletions or insertions at the repair site, which may disrupt or alter gene functionality.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Therefore, genomic engineering with CRISPR-Cas9 enables researchers to generate targeted random gene disruption.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] While genome editing in eukaryotic cells has been possible using various methods since the 1980s, the methods employed have proven to be inefficient and impractical for large-scale implementation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] With the discovery of CRISPR and specifically the Cas9 nuclease molecule, efficient and highly selective editing became possible.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas9, derived from the bacterial species *Streptococcus pyogenes,* has facilitated targeted genomic modification in eukaryotic cells by enabling a reliable method of creating a targeted break at a specific location as designated by the crRNA and tracrRNA guide strands.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Researchers can insert Cas9 and template RNA with ease in order to silence or cause point mutations at specific loci.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This has proven invaluable for quick and efficient mapping of genomic models and biological processes associated with various genes in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Newly engineered variants of the Cas9 nuclease that significantly reduce off-target activity have been developed.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing techniques have many potential applications.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The use of the CRISPR-Cas9-gRNA complex for genome editing was the AAAS's choice for Breakthrough of the Year in 2015.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Since 2015, CRISPR has been experimentally investigated on non-viable human embryos.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2019, the first humans were born from genome-edited embryos using the CRISPR technique, as a result of the controversial He Jiankui affair.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Several bioethical concerns have been raised about the prospect of using CRISPR for germline editing, especially the potential enabling of human eugenics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2023, the first drug making use of CRISPR gene editing, Exagamglogene autotemcel, sold under the brand name "Casgevy", was officially approved for use in the United Kingdom, to cure sickle-cell disease and beta thalassemia.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] On 2 December 2023, the Kingdom of Bahrain became the second country in the world to approve the use of Casgevy to treat sickle-cell anemia and beta thalassemia.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] On December 8, 2023, Casgevy received approval for use in the United States by the Food and Drug Administration.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In the early 2000s, German researchers began developing zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), synthetic proteins whose DNA-binding domains enable them to create double-stranded breaks in DNA at specific points.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] ZFNs have a higher precision and the advantage of being smaller than Cas9, but ZFNs are not as commonly used as CRISPR-based methods.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2010, synthetic nucleases called transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs) provided an easier way to target a double-stranded break to a specific location on the DNA strand.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Both zinc finger nucleases and TALENs require the design and creation of a custom protein for each targeted DNA sequence, which is a much more difficult and time-consuming process than that of designing guide RNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPRs are much easier to design because the process requires synthesizing only a short RNA sequence, a procedure that is already widely used for many other molecular biology techniques (e.g., creating oligonucleotide primers).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Whereas methods such as RNA interference (RNAi) do not fully suppress gene function, CRISPR, ZFNs, and TALENs provide full, irreversible gene knockout.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR can also target several DNA sites simultaneously simply by introducing different gRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In addition, the costs of employing CRISPR are relatively low.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2005, Alexander Bolotin at the French National Institute for Agricultural Research (INRA) discovered a CRISPR locus that contained novel Cas genes, significantly one that encoded a large protein known as Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2006, Eugene Koonin at the US National Center for Biotechnology Information, NCBI, proposed an explanation as to how CRISPR cascades as a bacterial immune system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2007, Philippe Horvath at Danisco France SAS displayed experimentally how CRISPR systems are an adaptive immune system and integrate new phage DNA into the CRISPR array, which is how they fight off the next wave of attacking phage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2012, the research team led by professor Jennifer Doudna (University of California, Berkeley) and professor Emmanuelle Charpentier (Umeå University) was the first group to identify, disclose, and file a patent application for the CRISPR-Cas9 system needed to edit DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] They also published their finding that CRISPR-Cas9 could be programmed with RNA to edit genomic DNA, now considered one of the most significant discoveries in the history of biology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] As of November 2013, SAGE Labs (part of Horizon Discovery group) had exclusive rights from one of those companies to produce and sell genetically engineered rats and non-exclusive rights for mouse and rabbit models.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] By 2015, Thermo Fisher Scientific had licensed intellectual property from ToolGen to develop CRISPR reagent kits.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] As of December 2014, patent rights to CRISPR were contested.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Several companies were formed to develop related drugs and research tools.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] As companies ramped up financing, doubts as to whether CRISPR could be quickly monetized were raised.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2014, Feng Zhang of the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard and nine others were awarded US patent number 8,697,359 over the use of CRISPR–Cas9 gene editing in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Although Charpentier and Doudna (referred to as CVC) were credited for the conception of CRISPR, the Broad Institute was the first to achieve a "reduction to practice" according to patent judges Sally Gardner Lane, James T.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The first set of patents was awarded to the Broad team in 2015, prompting attorneys for the CVC group to request the first interference proceeding.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Shortly after, the University of California filed an appeal of this ruling.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In 2019, the second interference dispute was opened.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This was in response to patent applications made by CVC that required the appeals board to determine the original inventor of the technology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The USPTO ruled in March 2022 against UC, stating that the Broad Institute was first to file.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The decision affected many of the licensing agreements for the CRISPR editing technology that was licensed from UC Berkeley.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] UC stated its intent to appeal the USPTO's ruling.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] As of August 2017, the patent situation in Europe was complex, with MilliporeSigma, ToolGen, Vilnius University, and Harvard contending for claims, along with the University of California and Broad.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In July 2018, the ECJ ruled that gene editing for plants was a sub-category of GMO foods and therefore that the CRISPR technique would henceforth be regulated in the European Union by their rules and regulations for GMOs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In February 2020, a US trial showed safe CRISPR gene editing on three cancer patients.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In October 2020, researchers Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their work in this field.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] They made history as the first two women to share this award without a male contributor.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In June 2021, the first, small clinical trial of intravenous CRISPR gene editing in humans concluded with promising results.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In September 2021, the first CRISPR-edited food went on public sale in Japan.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Tomatoes were genetically modified for around five times the normal amount of possibly calming GABA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR was first applied in tomatoes in 2014.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] A 2022 study has found that knowing more about CRISPR tomatoes had a strong effect on the participants' preference.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In May 2021, UC Berkeley announced their intent to auction non-fungible tokens of both the patent for CRISPR gene editing as well as cancer immunotherapy.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] However, the university would, in this case, retain ownership of the patents.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] 85% of the funds gathered through the sale of the collection named *The Fourth Pillar* were to be used to finance research.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It sold in June 2022 for 22 Ether, which was around US$54,000 at the time.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In November 2023, the United Kingdom's Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) became the first in the world to approve the use of the first drug based on CRISPR gene editing, Casgevy, to treat sickle-cell anemia and beta thalassemia.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Casgevy, or exagamglogene autotemcel, directly acts on the genes of the stem cells inside the patient's bones, having them produce healthy red blood cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This treatment thus avoids the need for regular, costly blood transfusions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] On 2 December 2023, the Kingdom of Bahrain's National Health Regulatory Authority (NHRA) became the second in the world to approve the use of Casgevy to treat sickle-cell anemia and beta thalassemia.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In December 2023, the FDA approved the first gene therapy in the US to treat patients with Sickle Cell Disease (SCD).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The FDA approved two milestone treatments, Casgevy and Lyfgenia, representing the first cell-based gene therapies for the treatment of SCD.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing uses a Type II CRISPR system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This system includes a ribonucleoprotein (RNP), consisting of Cas9, crRNA, and tracrRNA, along with an optional DNA repair template.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR-Cas9 often employs plasmids that code for the RNP components to transfect the target cells, or the RNP is assembled before addition to the cells via nucleofection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The main components of this plasmid are displayed in the image and listed in the table.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The crRNA is uniquely designed for each application, as this is the sequence that Cas9 uses to identify and directly bind to specific sequences within the host cell's DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The crRNA must bind only where editing is desired.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The repair template is also uniquely designed for each application, as it must complement to some degree the DNA sequences on either side of the cut and also contain whatever sequence is desired for insertion into the host genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Multiple crRNAs and the tracrRNA can be packaged together to form a single-guide RNA (sgRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This sgRNA can be included alongside the gene that codes for the Cas9 protein and made into a plasmid in order to be transfected into cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Many online tools are available to aid in designing effective sgRNA sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas12a (CRISPR-associated protein 12a, previously Cpf1) is a Class II Type V CRISPR-associated endonuclease-exonuclease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In bacteria such as *F. novicida,* its natural context, Cas12a targets and destroys the genetic material of viruses and other foreign mobile genetic elements.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] In a target organism, crRNA contains a constant region that Cas12a recognizes and a "spacer" region that is complementary to a piece of foreign nucleic acid (e.g., a portion of a phage genome) that previously infected the cell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Modified versions of Class II systems (specifically Cas12a) function with an artificial single-stranded DNA guide in place of natural RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Within this new paradigm, the system's endonuclease activity now is redirected towards cleaving ssRNA instead of dsDNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] With DNA as the guide, the need for intricate RNA preparation and preservation is no longer required, allowing Class II effectors more versatility in programmable RNA targeting and translational biotechnology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas13 is a family of orthologous CRISPR-associated endonucleases that target RNA (unlike Cas9 and Cas12, which target DNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas13 utilizes a single RNA-guided endonuclease to bind and cleave specific ssRNA sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It employs two distinct ribonuclease functions: one processes its own CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and another degrades the target RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The system's specificity allows for the correction of mutations at the transcript level.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas13 remains bound to the target and then cleaves other ssRNA molecules non-discriminately.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This collateral cleavage property is exploited in the development of various diagnostic technologies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Its PAM-independent targeting and reduced off-target effects make it suitable for RNA imaging, phage genome engineering, and transient gene regulation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR-Cas9 offers a high degree of fidelity and relatively simple construction.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It depends on two factors for its specificity: the target sequence and the protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The target sequence is 20 bases long as part of each CRISPR locus in the crRNA array.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] A typical crRNA array has multiple unique target sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas9 proteins select the correct location on the host's genome by utilizing the sequence to bond with base pairs on the host DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The sequence is not part of the Cas9 protein and as a result is customizable and can be independently synthesized.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The PAM sequence on the host genome is recognized by Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cas9 cannot be easily modified to recognize a different PAM sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] However, this is ultimately not too limiting, as it is typically a very short and nonspecific sequence that occurs frequently at many places throughout the genome (e.g. the SpCas9 PAM sequence is 5'-NGG-3' and in the human genome occurs roughly every 8 to 12 base pairs).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Once these sequences have been assembled into a plasmid and transfected into cells, the Cas9 protein with the help of the crRNA finds the correct sequence in the host cell's DNA and – depending on the Cas9 variant – creates a single- or double-stranded break at the appropriate location in the DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Properly spaced single-stranded breaks in the host DNA can trigger homology directed repair, which is less error-prone than the non-homologous end joining or theta-mediated end joining that typically follows a double-stranded break.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Providing a DNA repair template allows for the insertion of a specific DNA sequence at an exact location within the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The repair template should extend 40 to 90 base pairs beyond the Cas9-induced DNA break.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The goal is for the cell's native HDR process to utilize the provided repair template and thereby incorporate the new sequence into the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Once incorporated, this new sequence is now part of the cell's genetic material and passes into its daughter cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Combined transient inhibition of NHEJ and TMEJ by a small molecule and siRNAs can increase HDR efficiency to up to 93% and simultaneously prevent off-target editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Delivery of Cas9, sgRNA, and associated complexes into cells can occur via viral and non-viral systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Electroporation of DNA, RNA, or ribonucleocomplexes is a common technique, though it can result in harmful effects on the target cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Chemical transfection techniques utilizing lipids and peptides have also been used to introduce sgRNAs in complex with Cas9 into cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Nanoparticle-based delivery has also been used for transfection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Types of cells that are more difficult to transfect (e.g., stem cells, neurons, and hematopoietic cells) require more efficient delivery systems, such as those based on lentivirus (LVs), adenovirus (AdV), and adeno-associated virus (AAV).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Efficiency of CRISPR-Cas9 has been found to greatly increase when various components of the system including the entire CRISPR/Cas9 structure to Cas9-gRNA complexes delivered in assembled form rather than using transgenics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This has found particular value in genetically modified crops for mass commercialization.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Since the host's replication machinery is not needed to produce these proteins, the chance of the recognizing sequence of the sgRNA is almost none, decreasing the chance of off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Further improvements and variants of the CRISPR-Cas9 system have focused on introducing more control into its use.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Specifically, the research aimed at improving this system includes improving its specificity, its efficiency, and the granularity of its editing power.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Techniques can further be divided and classified by the component of the system they modify.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] These include using different variants or novel creations of the Cas protein, using an altogether different effector protein, modifying the sgRNA, or using an algorithmic approach to identify existing optimal solutions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Specificity is an important aspect to improve the CRISPR-Cas9 system because the off-target effects it generates have serious consequences for the genome of the cell and invokes caution for its use.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Minimizing off-target effects is thus maximizing the safety of the system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Novel variations of Cas9 proteins that increase specificity include effector proteins with comparable efficiency and specificity to the original SpCas9 that are able to target the previously untargetable sequences and a variant that has virtually no off-target mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Research has also been conducted in engineering new Cas9 proteins, including some that partially replace RNA nucleotides in crRNA with DNA and a structure-guided Cas9 mutant generating procedure that all had reduced off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Iteratively truncated sgRNAs and highly stabilized gRNAs have been shown to also decrease off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Computational methods including machine learning have been used to predict the affinity of and create unique sequences for the system to maximize specificity for given targets.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Several variants of CRISPR-Cas9 allow gene activation or genome editing with an external trigger such as light or small molecules.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Intein-inducible split-Cas9 allows dimerization of Cas9 fragments and rapamycin-inducible split-Cas9 system developed by fusing two constructs of split-Cas9 with FRB and FKBP fragments.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Other studies have been able to induce transcription of Cas9 with a small molecule, doxycycline.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Small molecules can also be used to improve homology directed repair, often by inhibiting the non-homologous end joining pathway and/or the theta-mediated end-joining pathway.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] A system with the Cpf1 effector protein was created that is induced by small molecules VE-822 and AZD-7762.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] These systems allow conditional control of CRISPR activity for improved precision, efficiency, and spatiotemporal control.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Spatiotemporal control is a form of removing off-target effects—only certain cells or parts of the organism may need to be modified, and thus light or small molecules can be used as a way to conduct this.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Efficiency of the CRISPR-Cas9 system is also greatly increased by proper delivery of the DNA instructions for creating the proteins and necessary reagents.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR also utilizes single base-pair editing proteins to create specific edits at one or two bases in the target sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR/Cas9 was fused with specific enzymes that initially could only change C to T and G to A mutations and their reverse.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This was accomplished eventually without requiring any DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] With the fusion of another enzyme, the base editing CRISPR-Cas9 system can also edit C to G and its reverse.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats (CRISPR)/Cas9 system is a gene-editing technology that can induce double-strand breaks (DSBs) anywhere guide ribonucleic acids (gRNA) can bind with the protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Single-strand nicks can also be induced by Cas9 active-site mutants, also known as Cas9 nickases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] By simply changing the sequence of gRNA, the Cas9-endonuclease can be delivered to a gene of interest and induce DSBs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The efficiency of Cas9-endonuclease and the ease by which genes can be targeted led to the development of CRISPR-knockout (KO) libraries both for mouse and human cells, which can cover either specific gene sets of interest or the whole genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] CRISPR screening helps scientists to create a systematic and high-throughput genetic perturbation within live model organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] This genetic perturbation is necessary for fully understanding gene function and epigenetic regulation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] The advantage of pooled CRISPR libraries is that more genes can be targeted at once.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Knock-out libraries are created in a way to achieve equal representation and performance across all expressed gRNAs and carry an antibiotic or fluorescent selection marker that can be used to recover transduced cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] There are two plasmid systems in CRISPR/Cas9 libraries.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] First, is all in one plasmid, where sgRNA and Cas9 are produced simultaneously in a transfected cell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Second, is a two-vector system: sgRNA and Cas9 plasmids are delivered separately.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Once a pooled library is prepared it is necessary to carry out a deep sequencing (NGS, next generation sequencing) of PCR-amplified plasmid DNA in order to reveal abundance of sgRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Cells of interest can be consequentially infected by the library and then selected according to the phenotype.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] There are 2 types of selection: negative and positive.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] By negative selection dead or slow growing cells are efficiently detected.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It can identify survival-essential genes, which can further serve as candidates for molecularly targeted drugs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] On the other hand, positive selection gives a collection of growth-advantage acquired populations by random mutagenesis.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] After selection genomic DNA is collected and sequenced by NGS.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Depletion or enrichment of sgRNAs is detected and compared to the original sgRNA library, annotated with the target gene that sgRNA corresponds to.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Statistical analysis then identifies genes that are significantly likely to be relevant to the phenotype of interest.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Apart from knock-out there are also knock-down (CRISPRi) and activation (CRISPRa) libraries, which use the ability of proteolytically deactivated Cas9-fusion proteins (dCas9) to bind target DNA, which means that a gene of interest is not cut but is over-expressed or repressed.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] It made CRISPR/Cas9 system even more interesting in gene editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] Inactive dCas9 protein modulate gene expression by targeting dCas9-repressors or activators toward promoter or transcriptional start sites of target genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p01] For repressing genes Cas9 can be fused to KRAB effector domain that makes complex with gRNA, whereas CRISPRa utilizes dCas9 fused to different transcriptional activation domains, which are further directed by gRNA to promoter regions to upregulate expression.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 genomic modification has allowed for the quick and efficient generation of transgenic models within the field of genetics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 can be easily introduced into the target cells along with sgRNA via plasmid transfection in order to model the spread of diseases and the cell's response to and defense against infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The ability of Cas9 to be introduced *in vivo* allows for the creation of more accurate models of gene function and mutation effects, all while avoiding the off-target mutations typically observed with older methods of genetic engineering.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The CRISPR and Cas9 revolution in genomic modeling does not extend only to mammals.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Traditional genomic models such as *Drosophila melanogaster*, one of the first model organisms, have seen further refinement in their resolution with the use of Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 uses cell-specific promoters allowing a controlled use of the Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 is an accurate method of treating diseases due to the targeting of the Cas9 enzyme only affecting certain cell types.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The cells undergoing the Cas9 therapy can also be removed and reintroduced to provide amplified effects of the therapy.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas9 can be used to edit the DNA of organisms *in vivo* and to eliminate individual genes or even entire chromosomes from an organism at any point in its development.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Chromosomes that have been successfully deleted *in vivo* using CRISPR techniques include the Y chromosome and X chromosome of adult lab mice and human chromosomes 14 and 21, in embryonic stem cell lines and aneuploid mice respectively.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This method might be useful for treating genetic disorders caused by abnormal numbers of chromosomes, such as Down syndrome and intersex disorders.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Successes have been achieved in the study of basic biology, in the creation of disease models, and in the experimental treatment of disease models.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Concerns have been raised that off-target effects (editing of genes besides the ones intended) may confound the results of a CRISPR gene editing experiment (i.e. the observed phenotype change may not be due to modifying the target gene, but some other gene).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Modifications to CRISPR have been made to minimize the possibility of off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Orthogonal CRISPR experiments are often recommended to confirm the results of a gene editing experiment.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR simplifies the creation of genetically modified organisms for research which mimic disease or show what happens when a gene is knocked down or mutated.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR may be used at the germline level to create organisms in which the targeted gene is changed everywhere (i.e. in all cells/tissues/organs of a multicellular organism), or it may be used in non-germline cells to create local changes that only affect certain cell populations within the organism.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR can be utilized to create human cellular models of disease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] For instance, when applied to human pluripotent stem cells, CRISPR has been used to introduce targeted mutations in genes relevant to polycystic kidney disease (PKD) and focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These CRISPR-modified pluripotent stem cells were subsequently grown into human kidney organoids that exhibited disease-specific phenotypes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Kidney organoids from stem cells with PKD mutations formed large, translucent cyst structures from kidney tubules.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The cysts were capable of reaching macroscopic dimensions, up to one centimeter in diameter.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Kidney organoids with mutations in a gene linked to FSGS developed junctional defects between podocytes, the filtering cells affected in that disease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This was traced to the inability of podocytes to form microvilli between adjacent cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Importantly, these disease phenotypes were absent in control organoids of identical genetic background, but lacking the CRISPR modifications.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] A similar approach was taken to model long QT syndrome in cardiomyocytes derived from pluripotent stem cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These CRISPR-generated cellular models, with isogenic controls, provide a new way to study human disease and test drugs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR editing can be used to define the molecular function of non-coding alleles associated with complex diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These alleles are ubiquitously associated with complex traits, and work by altering gene regulation in relevant cell-types.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] They are also very difficult to ascribe function too.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Genome editing can be used to introduce individual variants into the genome, and then downstream molecular effects can be defined.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This approach must be done in appropriate cell-types or cell lines for the variant of interest.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Also, this approach can be confounded by off-target effects, low efficiency editing, and non-specific transcriptional effects of gene editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas technology has been proposed as a treatment for multiple human diseases, especially those with a genetic cause.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Its ability to modify specific DNA sequences makes it a tool with potential to fix disease-causing mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR has also been used to cure malaria in mosquitos, which could eliminate the vector and the disease in humans.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR may also have applications in tissue engineering and regenerative medicine, such as by creating human blood vessels that lack expression of MHC class II proteins, which often cause transplant rejection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In addition, clinical trials to cure beta thalassemia and sickle cell disease in human patients using CRISPR-Cas9 technology have shown promising results.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In December 2023, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved the first cell-based gene therapies for treating sickle cell disease, Casgevy and Lyfgenia.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Casgevy is the first FDA approved gene therapy to use the CRISPR-Cas9 technology and works by modifying a patient's hematopoietic stem cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR has also found many applications in developing cell-based immunotherapies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The first clinical trial involving CRISPR started in 2016.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] It involved taking immune cells from people with lung cancer, using CRISPR to edit out the gene which expressed Programmed cell death protein 1 (PD-1), then administering the altered cells back to the same person.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] 20 other trials were under way or nearly ready, mostly in China, as of 2017.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2016, the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved a clinical trial in which CRISPR would be used to alter T cells extracted from people with different kinds of cancer and then administer those engineered T cells back to the same people.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In November 2020, in mouse animal models, CRISPR was used effectively to treat glioblastoma (fast-growing brain tumor) and metastatic ovarian cancer, as those are two cancers with some of the worst best-case prognosis and are typically diagnosed during their later stages.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The treatments have resulted in inhibited tumor growth, and increased survival by 80% for metastatic ovarian cancer and tumor cell apoptosis, inhibited tumor growth by 50%, and improved survival by 30% for glioblastoma.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In October 2021, CRISPR Therapeutics announced results from their ongoing US-based phase 1 trial for an allogeneic T cell therapy.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These cells are sourced from healthy donors and are edited to attack cancer cells and avoid being seen as a threat by the recipient's immune system, and then multiplied into huge batches which can be given to large numbers of recipients.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The procedure included reprogramming a healthy T-cell to destroy the cancerous T-cells to first rid her of leukaemia, and then rebuilding her immune system from scratch using healthy immune cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The team used BASE editing and had previously treated a case of acute lymphoblastic leukaemia in 2015 using TALENs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Type 1 diabetes is an endocrine disorder which results from a lack of pancreatic beta cells to produce insulin, a vital compound in transporting blood sugar to cells for producing energy.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Researchers have been trying to transplant healthy beta cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR is used to edit the cells in order to reduce the chance the patient's body will reject the transplant.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] On November 17, 2021 CRISPR therapeutics and ViaCyte announced that the Canadian medical agency had approved their request for a clinical trial for VCTX210, a CRISPR-edited stem cell therapy designed to treat type 1 diabetes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This was significant because it was the first ever gene-edited therapy for diabetes that approached clinics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The same companies also developed a novel treatment for type 1 diabetes to produce insulin via a small medical implant that uses millions of pancreatic cells derived from CRISPR gene-edited stem cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In February 2022, a phase 1 trial was conducted in which one patient volunteer received treatment.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) is a virus that attacks the body's immune system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] While effective treatments exist which can allow patients to live healthy lives, HIV is retroactive, meaning that it embeds an inactive version of itself in the human genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR can be used to selectively remove the virus from the genome by designing guide RNA to target the retroactive HIV genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] One issue with this approach is that it requires the removal of the HIV genome from almost all cells, which can be difficult to realistically achieve.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Initial results in the treatment and cure of HIV have been rather successful, in 2021 9 out of 23 humanized mice treated with a combination of anti-retrovirals and CRISPR/Cas-9 had the virus become undetectable, even after the usual rebound period.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] None of the two treatments alone had such an effect.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Clinical trials in humans of a CRISPR–Cas9 based therapy, EBT-101 started in 2022.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In October 2023 an early-stage study on 3 people of EBT-101 reported that the treatment appeared to be safe with no major side effects but no data on its effectiveness was disclosed.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In March 2024 another CRISPR therapy from researchers of the university of Amsterdam reported the elimination of HIV in cell cultures.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas-based "RNA-guided nucleases" can be used to target virulence factors, genes encoding antibiotic resistance, and other medically relevant sequences of interest.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This technology thus represents a novel form of antimicrobial therapy and a strategy by which to manipulate bacterial populations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Recent studies suggest a correlation between the interfering of the CRISPR-Cas locus and acquisition of antibiotic resistance.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This system provides protection of bacteria against invading foreign DNA, such as transposons, bacteriophages, and plasmids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This system was shown to be a strong selective pressure for the acquisition of antibiotic resistance and virulence factor in bacterial pathogens.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Therapies based on CRISPR–Cas3 gene editing technology delivered by engineered bacteriophages could be used to destroy targeted DNA in pathogens.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas3 is more destructive than the better known Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Research suggests that CRISPR is an effective way to limit replication of multiple herpesviruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] It was able to eradicate viral DNA in the case of Epstein–Barr virus (EBV).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Anti-herpesvirus CRISPRs have promising applications such as removing cancer-causing EBV from tumor cells, helping rid donated organs for immunocompromised patients of viral invaders, or preventing cold sore outbreaks and recurrent eye infections by blocking HSV-1 reactivation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] As of August 2016, these were awaiting testing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR may revive the concept of transplanting animal organs into people.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Retroviruses present in animal genomes could harm transplant recipients.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2015, a team eliminated 62 copies of a particular retroviral DNA sequence from the pig genome in a kidney epithelial cell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Researchers recently demonstrated the ability to birth live pig specimens after removing these retroviruses from their genome using CRISPR for the first time.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR can be used to suppress gain of function mutations and to repair loss of function mutations in neurological disorders.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The gene editing tool has become a foothold in vivo application for assimilation of molecular pathways.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR is unique to the development of solving neurological diseases for several reasons.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] For example, CRISPR allows researchers to quickly generate animal and human cell models, allowing them to study how genes function in a nervous system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] By introducing mutations that pertain to various diseases within these cells, researchers can study the effects of the changes on nervous system development, function, and behavior.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] They can uncover the molecular mechanisms that contribute to these disorders, which is essential for developing effective treatments.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This is particularly useful in modeling and treating complex neurological disorders such as Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, and epilepsy among others.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Alzheimer's Disease (AD) is a neurodegenerative disease categorized by neuron loss and an accumulation of intracellular neurofibrillary tangles and extracellular amyloid plaques in the brain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Three pathogenic genes that cause early onset AD in humans have been identified, specifically amyloid precursor protein (APP), presenilin 1 (PSEN1), and presenilin 2 (PSEN2).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Over 300 mutations have been detected in these genes, resulting in an increase in total β-amyloid (Aβ), Aβ42/40 ratio, and/or Aβ polymerization.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR has been used to correct for the dystrophin gene, which is responsible for Duchenne muscular dystrophy, and for the SCN1A mutation responsible for the epilepsy disorder Dravet syndrome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] A challenge of using CRISPR for neurological treatment is transferring its components across the blood-brain barrier.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] However, recent advancements in nanoparticle delivery systems and viral vectors have shown promise in overcoming this hurdle.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Looking to the future, the use of CRISPR in neuroscience is expected to increase as technology evolves.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The most commonly occurring worldwide eye diseases are cataract and retinitis pigmentosa (RP).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These are caused by a missense mutation in the alpha chain that leads to permanent blindness.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] A challenge to the use of CRISPR 77hh in eye disease is that retinal tissue in the eye is free from body immune response.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Researchers' approach for using CRISPR is to bag the gene coding retinal protein and edit the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The CRISPR treatment for LCA10 (the most common variant of Leber congenital amaurosis which is the leading cause of inherited childhood blindness) modifies the patient's defective photoreceptor gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In March 2020, the first patient volunteer in this US-based study, sponsored by Editas Medicine, was given a low-dose of the treatment to test for safety.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In June 2021, enrollment began for a high-dose adult and pediatric cohort of 4 patient volunteers each.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Dosing of the new cohorts was expected to be completed by July 2022.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In November 2022, Editas reported that 20% of the patients treated had significant improvements, but also announced that the resulting target population was too small to support continued independent development.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR technology has been shown to work efficiently in the treatment of heart disease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In the case of familial hypercholesterolemia (FH), cholesterol deposition in the walls of the artery causes blockage of blood flow.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This is caused by mutation in low density lipoprotein cholesterol receptors (LDLC) which results in excessive release of cholesterol into the blood.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This can be treated by deletion of a base pair in exon 4 of the LDLC receptor.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This disease comes under genetic disorders which are caused by mutation occurring in the structure of hemoglobin or due to substitution of different amino acids in globin chains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Due to this, the red blood cells (RBC) cause a string of obstacles such as heart failure, hindrance of blood vessels, defects in growth and optical problems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] To rehabilitate β-hemoglobinopathies, the patient's multipotent cells are transferred in a mice model to study the rate of gene therapy in ex-vivo which results in expression of mRNA and the gene being rectified.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Intriguingly RBC half-life was also increased.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Hemophilia is a loss of the clotting function in blood due to one of the clotting proteins not working properly.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] A research team created a line of mice that had the same defective clotting protein found in human Hemophilia B .
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] By using CRISPR-Cas9 the team was able to insert a gene for a working version of the defective protein into the liver cells of these mice.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Enough liver cells were repaired to alleviate the symptoms of heamophilia in these mice.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Successful CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing was first achieved in plants in August 2013.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] It has since been successfully applied in several key crop species for the purpose of introducing or improving numerous agricultural traits.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The development of CRISPR technology has been highly influential in the field of plant biotechnology, and has the potential to revolutionize the future of agriculture.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas systems are most commonly introduced into plants by Agrobacterium-mediated transformation, although particle bombardment and protoplast transformation are also used.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Improvement of crop yields has been achieved in several species through the use of CRISPR-Cas technology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Grain yield in cereal crops is influenced by levels of the plant hormone cytokinin.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] High-yielding rice and wheat varieties have been produced by using CRISPR-Cas9 to knock out the enzyme cytokinin oxidase/dehydrogenase (CKX), which degrades cytokinin.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Grain yield has also been increased in rice by using CRISPR-Cas9 to knock out an amino acid transporter.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR has been used to develop higher quality crops, including improvements to physical appearance, flavor and aroma, texture, shelf life, and nutritional content.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Pink, yellow, and purple tomatoes have been produced by using CRISPR to mutate genes involved in synthesizing pigments.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR has also been used to decrease starch content in wheat, thus improving grain quality.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In addition, soybeans have been modified using CRISPR to contain more heart-healthy monounsaturated fatty acids, like oleic acid.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR technology has also been used to reduce the amount of allergens in foods.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Wheat containing decreased levels of gluten, a common allergen and intolerance, has been developed using CRISPR.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Researchers are also working to reduce allergens in soybean, peanut, and mustard using CRISPR-Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR has been used to develop plants with improved resistance to various diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Using CRISPR, cucumber, rice, and tobacco plants have been engineered with resistance to viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Wheat, rice, tomato, grape, and cacao have been modified for resistance to fungal diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Finally, rice, apple, and citrus fruits have been developed with resistance to bacterial infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] There are currently about 6000 known genetic disorders, most of which are currently untreatable.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The role of CRISPR in gene therapy is to substitute exogenous DNA in place of defective genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Gene therapy has made a huge impact and opened many new possibilities in medical biotechnology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cytidine base editor is a novel therapy in which the cytidine (C) changes to thymidine (T).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Adenine base editor (ABE), in this there is a change in base complements from adenine (A) to Guanine (G).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The mutations were directly installed in cellular DNA so that the donor template is not required.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The base editings can only edit point mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Moreover, they can only fix up to four-point mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] To address this problem, the CRISPR system introduced a new technique known as Cas9 fusion to increase the scale of genes that can be edited.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Furthermore, the CRISPR Cas9 protein can modulate genes either by activating or silencing based on genes of interest.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] There is a nuclease called dCas9 (endonuclease) used to silence or activate the expression of genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The researchers are facing many challenges in gene editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The major hurdles coming in the clinical applications are ethical issues and the transport system to the target site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] As the units of CRISPR system taken from bacteria, when they are transferred to host cells it produces an immune response against them.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Physical, chemical, viral vectors are used as vehicles to deliver the complex into the host.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Due to this many complications are arising such as cell damage that leads to cell death.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In the case of viral vectors, the capacity of the virus is small and Cas9 protein is large.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] So, to overcome these new methods were developed in which smaller strains of Cas9 are taken from bacteria.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Finally, a great extent of work is still needed to improve the system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR associated nucleases have shown to be useful as a tool for molecular testing due to their ability to specifically target nucleic acid sequences in a high background of non-target sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2016, the Cas9 nuclease was used to deplete unwanted nucleotide sequences in next-generation sequencing libraries while requiring only 250 picograms of initial RNA input.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Beginning in 2017, CRISPR associated nucleases were also used for direct diagnostic testing of nucleic acids, down to single molecule sensitivity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR diversity is used as an analysis target to discern phylogeny and diversity in bacteria, such as in xanthomonads by Martins *et al.*, 2019.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Early detections of plant pathogens by molecular typing of the pathogen's CRISPRs can be used in agriculture as demonstrated by Shen *et al.*, 2020.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] By coupling CRISPR-based diagnostics to additional enzymatic processes, the detection of molecules beyond nucleic acids is possible.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] One example of a coupled technology is SHERLOCK-based Profiling of IN vitro Transcription (SPRINT).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] SPRINT can be used to detect a variety of substances, such as metabolites in patient samples or contaminants in environmental samples, with high throughput or with portable point-of-care devices.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas platforms are also being explored for detection and inactivation of SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Two different comprehensive diagnostic tests, AIOD-CRISPR and SHERLOCK test have been identified for SARS-CoV-2.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The SHERLOCK test is based on a fluorescently labelled press reporter RNA which has the ability to identify 10 copies per microliter.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The AIOD-CRISPR helps with robust and highly sensitive visual detection of the viral nucleic acid.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas9 can be used in investigating and identifying the genetic differences of humans to other apes, especially of the brain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] One study described a major impact of an archaic gene variant on neurodevelopment which may be an artefact of a CRISPR side effect, as it could not be replicated in a subsequent study.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Using "dead" versions of Cas9 (dCas9) eliminates CRISPR's DNA-cutting ability, while preserving its ability to target desirable sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Multiple groups added various regulatory factors to dCas9s, enabling them to turn almost any gene on or off or adjust its level of activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Like RNAi, CRISPR interference (CRISPRi) turns off genes in a reversible fashion by targeting, but not cutting a site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The targeted site is methylated, epigenetically modifying the gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This modification inhibits transcription.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These precisely placed modifications may then be used to regulate the effects on gene expressions and DNA dynamics after the inhibition of certain genome sequences within DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Within the past few years, epigenetic marks in different human cells have been closely researched and certain patterns within the marks have been found to correlate with everything ranging from tumor growth to brain activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Conversely, CRISPR-mediated activation (CRISPRa) promotes gene transcription.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 is an effective way of targeting and silencing specific genes at the DNA level.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In bacteria, the presence of Cas9 alone is enough to block transcription.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] For mammalian applications, a section of protein is added.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Its guide RNA targets regulatory DNA sequences called promoters that immediately precede the target gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 was used to carry synthetic transcription factors that activated specific human genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The technique achieved a strong effect by targeting multiple CRISPR constructs to slightly different locations on the gene's promoter.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2016, researchers demonstrated that CRISPR from an ordinary mouth bacterium could be used to edit RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The researchers searched databases containing hundreds of millions of genetic sequences for those that resembled CRISPR genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] They considered the fusobacterium *Leptotrichia shahii*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] It had a group of genes that resembled CRISPR genes, but with important differences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] When the researchers equipped other bacteria with these genes, which they called C2c2, they found that the organisms gained a novel defense.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] C2c2 has later been renamed to Cas13a to fit the standard nomenclature for Cas genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Many viruses encode their genetic information in RNA rather than DNA that they repurpose to make new viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Bacteria with Cas13 make molecules that can dismember RNA, destroying the virus.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Tailoring these genes opened any RNA molecule to editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR-Cas systems can also be employed for editing of micro-RNA and long-noncoding RNA genes in plants.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Directing edits to correct mutated sequences was first proposed and demonstrated in 1995.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This initial work used synthetic RNA antisense oligonucleotides complementary to a pre-mature stop codon mutation in a dystrophin sequence to activate A-to-I editing of the stop codon to a read through codon in a model xenopus cell system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] While this also led to nearby inadvertent A-to-I transitions, A to I (read as G) transitions can correct all three stop codons, but cannot create a stop codon.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Therefore, the changes led >25% correction of the targeted stop codon with read through to a downstream luciferase reporter sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Follow on work by Rosenthal achieved editing of mutated mRNA sequence in mammalian cell culture by directing an oligonucleotide linked to a cytidine deaminase to correct a mutated cystic fibrosis sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] More recently, CRISPR-Cas13 fused to deaminases has been employed to direct mRNA editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2022, therapeutic RNA editing for Cas7-11 was reported.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] It enables sufficiently targeted cuts and an early version of it was used for *in vitro* editing in 2021.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Unlike DNA editing, which is permanent, the effects of RNA editing − including potential off-target mutations in RNA − are transient and are not inherited.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] RNA editing is therefore considered to be less risky.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Furthermore, it may only require a guide RNA by using the ADAR protein already found in humans and many other eukaryotes' cells instead of needing to introduce a foreign protein into the body.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Gene drives may provide a powerful tool to restore balance of ecosystems by eliminating invasive species.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Concerns regarding efficacy, unintended consequences in the target species as well as non-target species have been raised particularly in the potential for accidental release from laboratories into the wild.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Scientists have proposed several safeguards for ensuring the containment of experimental gene drives including molecular, reproductive, and ecological.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Many recommend that immunization and reversal drives be developed in tandem with gene drives in order to overwrite their effects if necessary.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] There remains consensus that long-term effects must be studied more thoroughly particularly in the potential for ecological disruption that cannot be corrected with reversal drives.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Unenriched sequencing libraries often have abundant undesired sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Cas9 can specifically deplete the undesired sequences with double strand breakage with up to 99% efficiency and without significant off-target effects as seen with restriction enzymes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Treatment with Cas9 can deplete abundant rRNA while increasing pathogen sensitivity in RNA-seq libraries.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Epigenome editing or epigenome engineering is a type of genetic engineering in which the epigenome is modified at specific sites using engineered molecules targeted to those sites (as opposed to whole-genome modifications).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Whereas gene editing involves changing the actual DNA sequence itself, epigenetic editing involves modifying and presenting DNA sequences to proteins and other DNA binding factors that influence DNA function.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] By "editing" epigenomic features in this manner, researchers can determine the exact biological role of an epigenetic modification at the site in question.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The engineered proteins used for epigenome editing are composed of a DNA binding domain that targets specific sequences and an effector domain that modifies epigenomic features.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Currently, three major groups of DNA binding proteins have been predominantly used for epigenome editing: Zinc finger proteins, Transcription Activator-Like Effectors (TALEs) and nuclease deficient Cas9 fusions (CRISPR).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Targeted regulation of disease-related genes may enable novel therapies for many diseases, especially in cases where adequate gene therapies are not yet developed or are inappropriate.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] While transgenerational and population level consequences are not fully understood, it may become a major tool for applied functional genomics and personalized medicine.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] As with RNA editing, it does not involve genetic changes and their accompanying risks.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] One example of a potential functional use of epigenome editing was described in 2021: repressing Nav1.7 gene expression via CRISPR-dCas9 which showed therapeutic potential in three mouse models of chronic pain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2022, research assessed its usefulness in reducing tau protein levels, regulating a protein involved in Huntington's disease, targeting an inherited form of obesity, and Dravet syndrome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2024, a study about diabetic wound healing showed that the modification of histones through metylation could stimulate the productions of large-scale EVs (Extracellular vesicles) to reduce angiogenesis for diabetic foot ulcers, thus reducing death danger.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Combination of CRISPR-Cas9 with integrases enabled a technique for large edits without problematic double-stranded breaks, as demonstrated with PASTE in 2022.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The researchers reported it could be used to deliver genes as long as 36,000 DNA base pairs to several types of human cells and thereby potentially for treating diseases caused by a large number of mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Prime editing is a CRISPR refinement to precisely replace, insert, or delete sections of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR edits are generally inefficient, fairly error-prone, and can lack target specificity, which are significant problems for using the technology in medicine.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Prime editing cuts a single strand of targeted genomic DNA using a CRISPR nickase, then uses a tethered reverse transcriptase to add a desired sequence onto the cut DNA end that can be incorporated into the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] An associated guide RNA, called a pegRNA, contains both a sequence for determining the targeted genetic sequence and a template for the new DNA sequence to be incorporated into the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This mechanism for installing genome edits can be both highly efficient and precise, with low rates of unintended sequence incorporation errors like indels.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The independent pairing events for the target and template together help prevent off-target edits, which significantly increases targeting flexibility and editing specificity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Prime editing was developed by researchers at the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard in Massachusetts.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] As of March 2015, multiple groups had announced ongoing research with the intention of laying the foundations for applying CRISPR to human embryos for human germline engineering, including labs in the US, China, and the UK, as well as US biotechnology company OvaScience.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Scientists, including a CRISPR co-discoverer, urged a worldwide moratorium on applying CRISPR to the human germline, especially for clinical use.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] They said "scientists should avoid even attempting, in lax jurisdictions, germline genome modification for clinical application in humans" until the full implications "are discussed among scientific and governmental organizations".
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] These scientists support further low-level research on CRISPR and do not see CRISPR as developed enough for any clinical use in making heritable changes to humans.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In April 2015, Chinese scientists reported results of an attempt to alter the DNA of non-viable human embryos using CRISPR to correct a mutation that causes beta thalassemia, a lethal heritable disorder.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The study had previously been rejected by both *Nature* and *Science* in part because of ethical concerns.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The experiments resulted in successfully changing only some of the intended genes, and had off-target effects on other genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The researchers stated that CRISPR is not ready for clinical application in reproductive medicine.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In April 2016, Chinese scientists were reported to have made a second unsuccessful attempt to alter the DNA of non-viable human embryos using CRISPR – this time to alter the CCR5 gene to make the embryo resistant to HIV infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In December 2015, an International Summit on Human Gene Editing took place in Washington under the guidance of David Baltimore.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Members of national scientific academies of the US, UK, and China discussed the ethics of germline modification.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] They agreed to support basic and clinical research under certain legal and ethical guidelines.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] A specific distinction was made between somatic cells, where the effects of edits are limited to a single individual, and germline cells, where genome changes can be inherited by descendants.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Heritable modifications could have unintended and far-reaching consequences for human evolution, genetically (e.g. gene–environment interactions) and culturally (e.g. social Darwinism).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Altering of gametocytes and embryos to generate heritable changes in humans was defined to be irresponsible.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The group agreed to initiate an international forum to address such concerns and harmonize regulations across countries.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In February 2017, the United States National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (NASEM) Committee on Human Gene Editing published a report reviewing ethical, legal, and scientific concerns of genomic engineering technology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The conclusion of the report stated that heritable genome editing is impermissible now but could be justified for certain medical conditions; however, they did not justify the usage of CRISPR for enhancement.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In November 2018, Jiankui He announced that he had edited two human embryos to attempt to disable the gene for CCR5, which codes for a receptor that HIV uses to enter cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] He said that twin girls, Lulu and Nana, had been born a few weeks earlier.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] He said that the girls still carried functional copies of CCR5 along with disabled CCR5 (mosaicism) and were still vulnerable to HIV.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The work was widely condemned as unethical, dangerous, and premature.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] An international group of scientists called for a global moratorium on genetically editing human embryos.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Policy regulations for the CRISPR-Cas9 system vary around the globe.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In February 2016, British scientists were given permission by regulators to genetically modify human embryos by using CRISPR-Cas9 and related techniques.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] However, researchers were forbidden from implanting the embryos and the embryos were to be destroyed after seven days.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The US has an elaborate, interdepartmental regulatory system to evaluate new genetically modified foods and crops.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] The act regulates any genetically modified organism that utilizes the genome of a predefined "plant pest" or any plant not previously categorized.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2015, Yinong Yang successfully deactivated 16 specific genes in the white button mushroom to make them non-browning.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Since he had not added any foreign-species (transgenic) DNA to his organism, the mushroom could not be regulated by the USDA under Section 340.2.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] Yang's white button mushroom was the first organism genetically modified with the CRISPR-Cas9 protein system to pass US regulation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2016, the USDA sponsored a committee to consider future regulatory policy for upcoming genetic modification techniques.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] With the help of the US National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, special interests groups met on April 15 to contemplate the possible advancements in genetic engineering within the next five years and any new regulations that might be needed as a result.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2017, the Food and Drug Administration proposed a rule that would classify genetic engineering modifications to animals as "animal drugs", subjecting them to strict regulation if offered for sale and reducing the ability for individuals and small businesses to make them profitable.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In China, where social conditions sharply contrast with those of the West, genetic diseases carry a heavy stigma.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] This leaves China with fewer policy barriers to the use of this technology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2012 and 2013, CRISPR was a runner-up in *Science Magazine*'s Breakthrough of the Year award.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2015, it was the winner of that award.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] CRISPR was named as one of *MIT Technology Review*'s 10 breakthrough technologies in 2014 and 2016.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2016, Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier, along with Rodolphe Barrangou, Philippe Horvath, and Feng Zhang won the Gairdner International award.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2017, Doudna and Charpentier were awarded the Japan Prize in Tokyo, Japan for their revolutionary invention of CRISPR-Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr-gene-editing-p02] In 2016, Charpentier, Doudna, and Zhang won the Tang Prize in Biopharmaceutical Science.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cas9 (or "CRISPR-associated protein 9") is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and open up specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within living organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This editing process has a wide variety of applications including basic biological research, development of biotechnological products, and treatment of diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The development of the CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing technique was recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2020 awarded to Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The discovery of clustered DNA repeats took place independently in three parts of the world.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The first description of what would later be called CRISPR is Ishino, et al. in 1987.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] They accidentally cloned part of a CRISPR sequence together with the iap *gene* *(*isozyme conversion of alkaline phosphatase*)* from *Escherichia coli*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The organization of the repeats surprised them, as clustered repeated sequences are more typically arranged consecutively, without interspersing sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 1993, van Solingen et al., published two articles about a cluster of interrupted direct repeats (DR) in that bacterium.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The team recognized the diversity of the sequences that intervened in the direct repeats among different strains of *M. tuberculosis* and used this property to design a typing method called *spoligotyping*, which remains in use.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Mojica studied the function of repeats in the archaeal genera *Haloferax* and *Haloarcula*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Mojica's supervisor surmised that the clustered repeats had a role in segregating replicated DNA into daughter cells during cell division, because plasmids and chromosomes with identical repeat arrays could not coexist in *Haloferax volcanii*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] They noted the transcription of the interrupted repeats for the first time; CRISPR's first full characterization.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] By 2000, Mojica and his students, after an automated search of published genomes, identified interrupted repeats in 20 species of microbes as belonging to the same family.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Because those sequences were interspaced, Mojica initially called these sequences "short regularly spaced repeats" (SRSR).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2001, Mojica and Jansen, who were searching for additional interrupted repeats, proposed the acronym CRISPR (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) to encompass the numerous acronyms then in use.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2002, Tang, et al. showed evidence that CRISPR repeat regions in *Archaeoglobus fulgidus* were transcribed into long RNA molecules subsequently processed into unit-length small RNAs, plus some longer forms of 2, 3, or more spacer-repeat units.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2005, Barrangou discovered that *S thermophilus*, after iterative phage infection challenges, develops increased phage resistance due to the incorporation of additional CRISPR spacer sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A major advance came with Jansen's observation that the prokaryote repeat cluster was accompanied by four homologous genes, CRISPR-associated systems, *Cas* 1–4.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The Cas proteins showed helicase and nuclease motifs, suggesting a role in the dynamic structure of the CRISPR loci.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, CRISPR's function remained enigmatic.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2005, three independent research groups showed that some CRISPR spacers are derived from phage DNA and extrachromosomal DNA such as plasmids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In effect, the spacers are fragments of DNA gathered from viruses that previously attacked the cell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The source of the spacers was a sign that the CRISPR-*cas* system could have a role in adaptive immunity in bacteria.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] All three studies proposing this idea were initially rejected by high-profile journals, but eventually appeared elsewhere.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The first publication proposing a role of CRISPR-Cas in microbial immunity, by Mojica, et al., predicted a role for the RNA transcript of spacers on target recognition in a mechanism that could be analogous to the RNA interference system used by eukaryotic cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Koonin and colleagues extended this RNA interference hypothesis by proposing mechanisms of action for the different CRISPR-Cas subtypes according to the predicted function of their proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Experimental work by several groups revealed the basic mechanisms of CRISPR-Cas immunity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2007, the first experimental evidence that CRISPR was part of the adaptive immune system was published.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A CRISPR region in *Streptococcus thermophilus* acquired spacers from the DNA of an infecting bacteriophage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The researchers manipulated the resistance of *S. thermophilus* to different types of phages by adding and deleting spacers whose sequence matched those found in the phages.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2008, Brouns and Van der Oost identified a complex of Cas proteins called Cascade, that in *E. coli* cut the CRISPR RNA precursor within the repeats into mature spacer-containing RNA molecules called CRISPR RNA (crRNA), which remained bound to the protein complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cascade, crRNA and a helicase/nuclease (Cas3) were required to provide a bacterial host with immunity against infection by a DNA virus.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] By designing an anti-virus CRISPR, they demonstrated that two orientations of the crRNA (sense/antisense) provided immunity, indicating that the crRNA guides were targeting dsDNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] That year Marraffini and Sontheimer confirmed that a CRISPR sequence of *S. epidermidis* targeted DNA and not RNA to prevent conjugation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This finding was at odds with the proposed RNA-interference-like mechanism of CRISPR-Cas immunity, although a CRISPR-Cas system that targets foreign RNA was later found in *Pyrococcus furiosus*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A 2010 study reported that CRISPR-Cas cuts strands of both phage and plasmid DNA in *S. thermophilus*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2012, Jinek et al. fused crRNA and tracrRNA into a single-guide RNA, simplifying Cas9 targeting. Šikšnys, et al., reported that Cas9 from *S. thermophilus* can target specific DNA by altering crRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2013, Cong, et al., as well as Mali, et al., applied CRISPR-Cas9 to edit human cell cultures.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In 2015, Liang, et al., edited human tripronuclear zygotes, achieving successful cleavage in 28 of 54 embryos.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Originally introduced by the Jain lab in pre-print, modified versions of Class II systems (specifically Cas12a) function with an artificial single-stranded DNA guide in place of natural RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The CRISPR array is made up of an AT-rich leader sequence followed by short repeats that are separated by unique spacers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR repeats typically range in size from 28 to 37 base pairs (bps), though there can be as few as 23 bp and as many as 55 bp.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Some show dyad symmetry, implying the formation of a secondary structure such as a stem-loop ('hairpin') in the RNA, while others are designed to be unstructured.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The size of spacers in different CRISPR arrays is typically 32 to 38 bp (range 21 to 72 bp).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] New spacers can appear rapidly as part of the immune response to phage infection.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] There are usually fewer than 50 units of the repeat-spacer sequence in a CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Small clusters of *cas* genes are often located next to CRISPR repeat-spacer arrays.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Collectively the 93 *cas* genes are grouped into 35 families based on sequence similarity of the encoded proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] 11 of the 35 families form the *cas* core, which includes the protein families Cas1 through Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A complete CRISPR-Cas locus has at least one gene belonging to the *cas* core.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR-Cas systems fall into two classes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Class 1 systems use a complex of multiple Cas proteins to degrade foreign nucleic acids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Class 2 systems use a single large Cas protein for the same purpose.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Class 1 is divided into types I, III, and IV; class 2 is divided into types II, V, and VI.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The 6 system types are divided into 33 subtypes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Each type and most subtypes are characterized by a "signature gene" found almost exclusively in the category.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Classification is also based on the complement of *cas* genes that are present.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Most CRISPR-Cas systems have a Cas1 protein.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The phylogeny of Cas1 proteins generally agrees with the classification system, but exceptions exist due to module shuffling.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Many organisms contain multiple CRISPR-Cas systems suggesting that they are compatible and may share components.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The sporadic distribution of the CRISPR-Cas subtypes suggests that the CRISPR-Cas system is subject to horizontal gene transfer during microbial evolution.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR-Cas immunity is a natural process of bacteria and archaea.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR-Cas prevents bacteriophage infection, conjugation and natural transformation by degrading foreign nucleic acids that enter the cell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] When a microbe is invaded by a bacteriophage, the first stage of the immune response is to capture phage DNA and insert it into a CRISPR locus in the form of a spacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cas1 and Cas2 are found in both types of CRISPR-Cas immune systems, which indicates that they are involved in spacer acquisition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Mutation studies confirmed this hypothesis, showing that removal of Cas1 or Cas2 stopped spacer acquisition, without affecting CRISPR immune response.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Multiple Cas1 proteins have been characterised and their structures resolved.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cas1 proteins have diverse amino acid sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, their crystal structures are similar and all purified Cas1 proteins are metal-dependent nucleases/integrases that bind to DNA in a sequence-independent manner.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Representative Cas2 proteins have been characterised and possess either (single strand) ssRNA- or (double strand) dsDNA- specific endoribonuclease activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In the I-E system of *E. coli*, Cas1 and Cas2 form a complex where a Cas2 dimer bridges two Cas1 dimers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In this complex, Cas2 performs a non-enzymatic scaffolding role, binding double-stranded fragments of invading DNA, while Cas1 binds the single-stranded flanks of the DNA and catalyses their integration into CRISPR arrays.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] New spacers are usually added at the beginning of the CRISPR next to the leader sequence creating a chronological record of viral infections.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In *E. coli* a histone like protein called integration host factor (IHF), which binds to the leader sequence, is responsible for the accuracy of this integration.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Bioinformatic analysis of regions of phage genomes that were excised as spacers (termed protospacers) revealed that they were not randomly selected but instead were found adjacent to short (3–5 bp) DNA sequences termed protospacer adjacent motifs (PAM).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Analysis of CRISPR-Cas systems showed PAMs to be important for type I and type II, but not type III systems during acquisition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In type I and type II systems, protospacers are excised at positions adjacent to a PAM sequence, with the other end of the spacer cut using a ruler mechanism, thus maintaining the regularity of the spacer size in the CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The conservation of the PAM sequence differs between CRISPR-Cas systems and appears to be evolutionarily linked to Cas1 and the leader sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] New spacers are added to a CRISPR array in a directional manner, occurring preferentially, but not exclusively, adjacent to the leader sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Analysis of the type I-E system from *E. coli* demonstrated that the first direct repeat adjacent to the leader sequence is copied, with the newly acquired spacer inserted between the first and second direct repeats.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The PAM sequence appears to be important during spacer insertion in type I-E systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] That sequence contains a strongly conserved final nucleotide (nt) adjacent to the first nt of the protospacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This nt becomes the final base in the first direct repeat.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This suggests that the spacer acquisition machinery generates single-stranded overhangs in the second-to-last position of the direct repeat and in the PAM during spacer insertion.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, not all CRISPR-Cas systems appear to share this mechanism as PAMs in other organisms do not show the same level of conservation in the final position.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It is likely that in those systems, a blunt end is generated at the very end of the direct repeat and the protospacer during acquisition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Analysis of *Sulfolobus solfataricus* CRISPRs revealed further complexities to the canonical model of spacer insertion, as one of its six CRISPR loci inserted new spacers randomly throughout its CRISPR array, as opposed to inserting closest to the leader sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Multiple CRISPRs contain many spacers to the same phage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The mechanism that causes this phenomenon was discovered in the type I-E system of *E. coli*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A significant enhancement in spacer acquisition was detected where spacers already target the phage, even mismatches to the protospacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This 'priming' requires the Cas proteins involved in both acquisition and interference to interact with each other.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Newly acquired spacers that result from the priming mechanism are always found on the same strand as the priming spacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This observation led to the hypothesis that the acquisition machinery slides along the foreign DNA after priming to find a new protospacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR-RNA (crRNA), which later guides the Cas nuclease to the target during the interference step, must be generated from the CRISPR sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The crRNA is initially transcribed as part of a single long transcript encompassing much of the CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This transcript is then cleaved by Cas proteins to form crRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The mechanism to produce crRNAs differs among CRISPR-Cas systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In type I-E and type I-F systems, the proteins Cas6e and Cas6f respectively, recognise stem-loops created by the pairing of identical repeats that flank the crRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] These Cas proteins cleave the longer transcript at the edge of the paired region, leaving a single crRNA along with a small remnant of the paired repeat region.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Type III systems also use Cas6, however, their repeats do not produce stem-loops.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cleavage instead occurs by the longer transcript wrapping around the Cas6 to allow cleavage just upstream of the repeat sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Type II systems lack the Cas6 gene and instead utilize RNaseIII for cleavage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Functional type II systems encode an extra small RNA that is complementary to the repeat sequence, known as a trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Transcription of the tracrRNA and the primary CRISPR transcript results in base pairing and the formation of dsRNA at the repeat sequence, which is subsequently targeted by RNaseIII to produce crRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Unlike the other two systems, the crRNA does not contain the full spacer, which is instead truncated at one end.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CrRNAs associate with Cas proteins to form ribonucleotide complexes that recognize foreign nucleic acids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CrRNAs show no preference between the coding and non-coding strands, which is indicative of an RNA-guided DNA-targeting system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The type I-E complex (commonly referred to as Cascade) requires five Cas proteins bound to a single crRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] During the interference stage in type I systems, the PAM sequence is recognized on the crRNA-complementary strand and is required along with crRNA annealing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In type I systems correct base pairing between the crRNA and the protospacer signals a conformational change in Cascade that recruits Cas3 for DNA degradation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Type II systems rely on a single multifunctional protein, Cas9, for the interference step.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Cas9 requires both the crRNA and the tracrRNA to function and cleave DNA using its dual HNH and RuvC/RNaseH-like endonuclease domains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Basepairing between the PAM and the phage genome is required in type II systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, the PAM is recognized on the same strand as the crRNA (the opposite strand to type I systems).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Type III systems, like type I require six or seven Cas proteins binding to crRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The type III systems analysed from *S. solfataricus* and *P. furiosus* both target the mRNA of phages rather than phage DNA genome, which may make these systems uniquely capable of targeting RNA-based phage genomes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Type III systems were also found to target DNA in addition to RNA using a different Cas protein in the complex, Cas10.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The DNA cleavage was shown to be transcription dependent.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The mechanism for distinguishing self from foreign DNA during interference is built into the crRNAs and is therefore likely common to all three systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Throughout the distinctive maturation process of each major type, all crRNAs contain a spacer sequence and some portion of the repeat at one or both ends.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It is the partial repeat sequence that prevents the CRISPR-Cas system from targeting the chromosome as base pairing beyond the spacer sequence signals self and prevents DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] RNA-guided CRISPR enzymes are classified as type V restriction enzymes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The cas genes in the adaptor and effector modules of the CRISPR-Cas system are believed to have evolved from two different ancestral modules.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A transposon-like element called casposon encoding the Cas1-like integrase and potentially other components of the adaptation module was inserted next to the ancestral effector module, which likely functioned as an independent innate immune system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The highly conserved cas1 and cas2 genes of the adaptor module evolved from the ancestral module while a variety of class 1 effector cas genes evolved from the ancestral effector module.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The evolution of these various class 1 effector module cas genes was guided by various mechanisms, such as duplication events.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] On the other hand, each type of class 2 effector module arose from subsequent independent insertions of mobile genetic elements.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] These mobile genetic elements took the place of the multiple gene effector modules to create single gene effector modules that produce large proteins which perform all the necessary tasks of the effector module.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The spacer regions of CRISPR-Cas systems are taken directly from foreign mobile genetic elements and thus their long-term evolution is hard to trace.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The non-random evolution of these spacer regions has been found to be highly dependent on the environment and the particular foreign mobile genetic elements it contains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR-Cas can immunize bacteria against certain phages and thus halt transmission.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] For this reason, Koonin described CRISPR-Cas as a Lamarckian inheritance mechanism.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, this was disputed by a critic who noted, "We should remember [Lamarck] for the good he contributed to science, not for things that resemble his theory only superficially.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Indeed, thinking of CRISPR and other phenomena as Lamarckian only obscures the simple and elegant way evolution really works".
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] But as more recent studies have been conducted, it has become apparent that the acquired spacer regions of CRISPR-Cas systems are indeed a form of Lamarckian evolution because they are genetic mutations that are acquired and then passed on.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] On the other hand, the evolution of the Cas gene machinery that facilitates the system evolves through classic Darwinian evolution.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Analysis of CRISPR sequences revealed coevolution of host and viral genomes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The basic model of CRISPR evolution is newly incorporated spacers driving phages to mutate their genomes to avoid the bacterial immune response, creating diversity in both the phage and host populations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] To resist a phage infection, the sequence of the CRISPR spacer must correspond perfectly to the sequence of the target phage gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Phages can continue to infect their hosts' given point mutations in the spacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Similar stringency is required in PAM or the bacterial strain remains phage sensitive.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A study of 124 *S. thermophilus* strains showed that 26% of all spacers were unique and that different CRISPR loci showed different rates of spacer acquisition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Some CRISPR loci evolve more rapidly than others, which allowed the strains' phylogenetic relationships to be determined.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A comparative genomic analysis showed that *E. coli* and *S. enterica* evolve much more slowly than *S. thermophilus*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The latter's strains that diverged 250,000 years ago still contained the same spacer complement.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Metagenomic analysis of two acid-mine-drainage biofilms showed that one of the analyzed CRISPRs contained extensive deletions and spacer additions versus the other biofilm, suggesting a higher phage activity/prevalence in one community than the other.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In the oral cavity, a temporal study determined that 7–22% of spacers were shared over 17 months within an individual while less than 2% were shared across individuals.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] From the same environment, a single strain was tracked using PCR primers specific to its CRISPR system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Broad-level results of spacer presence/absence showed significant diversity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, this CRISPR added three spacers over 17 months, suggesting that even in an environment with significant CRISPR diversity some loci evolve slowly.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPRs were analysed from the metagenomes produced for the Human Microbiome Project.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Although most were body-site specific, some within a body site are widely shared among individuals.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] One of these loci originated from streptococcal species and contained ≈15,000 spacers, 50% of which were unique.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Similar to the targeted studies of the oral cavity, some showed little evolution over time.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR evolution was studied in chemostats using *S. thermophilus* to directly examine spacer acquisition rates.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In one week, *S. thermophilus* strains acquired up to three spacers when challenged with a single phage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] During the same interval, the phage developed single-nucleotide polymorphisms that became fixed in the population, suggesting that targeting had prevented phage replication absent these mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Another *S. thermophilus* experiment showed that phages can infect and replicate in hosts that have only one targeting spacer.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Yet another showed that sensitive hosts can exist in environments with high-phage titres.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The chemostat and observational studies suggest many nuances to CRISPR and phage (co)evolution.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPRs are widely distributed among bacteria and archaea and show some sequence similarities.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Their most notable characteristic is their repeating spacers and direct repeats.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This characteristic makes CRISPRs easily identifiable in long sequences of DNA, since the number of repeats decreases the likelihood of a false positive match.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Analysis of CRISPRs in metagenomic data is more challenging, as CRISPR loci do not typically assemble, due to their repetitive nature or through strain variation, which confuses assembly algorithms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Where many reference genomes are available, polymerase chain reaction (PCR) can be used to amplify CRISPR arrays and analyse spacer content.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, this approach yields information only for specifically targeted CRISPRs and for organisms with sufficient representation in public databases to design reliable polymerase PCR primers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Degenerate repeat-specific primers can be used to amplify CRISPR spacers directly from environmental samples; amplicons containing two or three spacers can be then computationally assembled to reconstruct long CRISPR arrays.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The alternative is to extract and reconstruct CRISPR arrays from shotgun metagenomic data.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This is computationally more difficult, particularly with second generation sequencing technologies (e.g.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] 454, Illumina), as the short read lengths prevent more than two or three repeat units appearing in a single read.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Another way for bacteria to defend against phage infection is by having chromosomal islands.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] A subtype of chromosomal islands called phage-inducible chromosomal island (PICI) is excised from a bacterial chromosome upon phage infection and can inhibit phage replication.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] PICIs are induced, excised, replicated, and finally packaged into small capsids by certain staphylococcal temperate phages.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] PICIs use several mechanisms to block phage reproduction.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In the first mechanism, PICI-encoded Ppi differentially blocks phage maturation by binding or interacting specifically with phage TerS, hence blocking phage TerS/TerL complex formation responsible for phage DNA packaging.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In the second mechanism PICI CpmAB redirects the phage capsid morphogenetic protein to make 95% of SaPI-sized capsid and phage DNA can package only 1/3rd of their genome in these small capsids and hence become nonviable phage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The third mechanism involves two proteins, PtiA and PtiB, that target the LtrC, which is responsible for the production of virion and lysis proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This interference mechanism is modulated by a modulatory protein, PtiM, binds to one of the interference-mediating proteins, PtiA, and hence achieves the required level of interference.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] One study showed that lytic ICP1 phage, which specifically targets *Vibrio cholerae* serogroup O1, has acquired a CRISPR-Cas system that targets a *V. cholera* PICI-like element.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] The system has 2 CRISPR loci and 9 Cas genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It seems to be homologous to the I-F system found in *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Moreover, like the bacterial CRISPR-Cas system, ICP1 CRISPR-Cas can acquire new sequences, which allows phage and host to co-evolve.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Certain archaeal viruses were shown to carry mini-CRISPR arrays containing one or two spacers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It has been shown that spacers within the virus-borne CRISPR arrays target other viruses and plasmids, suggesting that mini-CRISPR arrays represent a mechanism of heterotypic superinfection exclusion and participate in interviral conflicts.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] CRISPR gene editing is a revolutionary technology that allows for precise, targeted modifications to the DNA of living organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Developed from a natural defense mechanism found in bacteria, CRISPR-Cas9 is the most commonly used system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] Gene editing with CRISPR-Cas9 involves a Cas9 nuclease and an engineered guide RNA, which come together to allow for the precise "cutting" of one or both strands of DNA at specific locations within the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It makes use of the cell's natural DNA repair systems, including non-homologous end joining, homology-directed repair, or mismatch repair, to modify, insert, or delete genetic material at these specific cut sites.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] This technology has transformed fields such as genetics, medicine, and agriculture, offering potential treatments for genetic disorders, advancements in crop engineering, and research into the fundamental workings of life.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] However, its ethical implications and potential unintended consequences have sparked significant debate.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] In February of 2025 the first case of CRISPR gene editing therapy on a child was documented.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It was used to treat Severe Carbamoyl Phosphate Synthetase 1 Deficiency.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/crispr] It was administered At Children's Hospital of Philadelphia and is currently successful in its use to counteract the disease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The development of CRISPR gene editing in 2015 improved the efficiency, specificity, and practicality of large-scale genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Since 2015, genome editing has been experimentally investigated on non-viable human embryos.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Genome editing was pioneered in the 1990s, before the advent of the common current nuclease-based gene-editing platforms, but its use was limited by low efficiencies of editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Genome editing with engineered nucleases, i.e. all three major classes of these enzymes—zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs) and engineered meganucleases—were selected by *Nature Methods* as the 2011 Method of the Year.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The CRISPR-Cas system was selected by *Science* as 2015 Breakthrough of the Year.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] As of 2015, four families of engineered nucleases were used: meganucleases, zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), transcription activator-like effector-based nucleases (TALEN), and the clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats (CRISPR/Cas9) system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Nine genome editors were available as of 2017.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In 2018, the common methods for such editing used engineered nucleases, or "molecular scissors".
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] These nucleases create site-specific double-strand breaks (DSBs) at desired locations in the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The induced double-strand breaks are repaired through nonhomologous end-joining (NHEJ) or homologous recombination (HR), resulting in targeted mutations ('edits').
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] A cautionary perspective on the possible blind spots and risks of CRISPR and related biotechnologies has been recently discussed, focusing on the stochastic nature of cellular control processes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The University of Edinburgh Roslin Institute engineered pigs resistant to a virus that causes porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome, which costs US and European pig farmers $2.6 billion annually.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In February 2020, a US trial safely showed CRISPR gene editing on 3 cancer patients.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In 2020 Sicilian Rouge High GABA, a tomato that makes more of an amino acid said to promote relaxation, was approved for sale in Japan.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In 2021, England (not the rest of the UK) planned to remove restrictions on gene-edited plants and animals, moving from European Union-compliant regulation to rules closer to those of the US and some other countries.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] An April 2021 European Commission report found "strong indications" that the current regulatory regime was not appropriate for gene editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Later in 2021, researchers announced a CRISPR alternative, labelled obligate mobile element–guided activity (OMEGA) proteins including IscB, IsrB and TnpB as endonucleases found in transposons, and guided by small ωRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Genetic engineering, as method of introducing new genetic elements into organisms, has been around since the 1970s.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] One drawback of this technology has been the random nature with which the DNA is inserted into the host's genome, which can impair or alter other genes within the organism.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] However, several methods have been discovered that target the inserted genes to specific sites within an organism's genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It has also enabled the editing of specific sequences within a genome, as well as reduced off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This could be used for research purposes, by targeting mutations to specific genes, and in gene therapy.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] By inserting a functional gene into an organism, and targeting it to replace the defective one, it could be possible to cure certain genetic diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Early methods to target genes to certain sites within a genome of an organism (called gene targeting) relied on homologous recombination (HR).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] By creating DNA constructs that contain a template that matches the targeted genome sequence, it is possible that the HR processes within the cell will insert the construct at the desired location.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Using this method on embryonic stem cells led to the development of transgenic mice with targeted genes knocked out.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It has also been possible to knock in genes or alter gene expression patterns.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In recognition of their discovery of how homologous recombination can be used to introduce genetic modifications in mice through embryonic stem cells, Mario Capecchi, Martin Evans and Oliver Smithies were awarded the 2007 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] If a vital gene is knocked out, it can prove lethal to the organism.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In order to study the function of these genes, site specific recombinases (SSR) were used.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The two most common types are the Cre-LoxP and Flp-FRT systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Cre recombinase is an enzyme that removes DNA by homologous recombination between binding sequences known as Lox-P sites.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The Flip-FRT system operates in a similar way, with the Flip recombinase recognising FRT sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] By crossing an organism containing the recombinase sites flanking the gene of interest with an organism that express the SSR under control of tissue specific promoters, it is possible to knock out or switch on genes only in certain cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] These techniques were also used to remove marker genes from transgenic animals.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Further modifications of these systems allowed researchers to induce recombination only under certain conditions, allowing genes to be knocked out or expressed at desired times or stages of development.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] A common form of genome editing relies on the concept of DNA double stranded break (DSB) repair mechanics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] There are two major pathways that repair DSB; non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) and homology directed repair (HDR).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] NHEJ uses a variety of enzymes to directly join the DNA ends, while the more accurate HDR uses a homologous sequence as a template for regeneration of missing DNA sequences at the break point.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This can be exploited by creating a vector with the desired genetic elements within a sequence that is homologous to the flanking sequences of a DSB.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This will result in the desired change being inserted at the site of the DSB.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] While HDR based gene editing is similar to the homologous recombination based gene targeting, the rate of recombination is increased by at least three orders of magnitude.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The key to genome editing is creating a DSB at a specific point within the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Commonly used restriction enzymes are effective at cutting DNA, but generally recognize and cut at multiple sites.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] To overcome this challenge and create site-specific DSB, three distinct classes of nucleases have been discovered and bioengineered to date.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] These are the Zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), transcription-activator like effector nucleases (TALEN), meganucleases and the clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats (CRISPR/Cas9) system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Meganucleases, discovered in the late 1980s, are enzymes in the endonuclease family which are characterized by their capacity to recognize and cut large DNA sequences (from 14 to 40 base pairs).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The most widespread and best known meganucleases are the proteins in the LAGLIDADG family, which owe their name to a conserved amino acid sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Meganucleases, found commonly in microbial species, have the unique property of having very long recognition sequences (>14bp) thus making them naturally very specific.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] However, there is virtually no chance of finding the exact meganuclease required to act on a chosen specific DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] To overcome this challenge, mutagenesis and high throughput screening methods have been used to create meganuclease variants that recognize unique sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Others have been able to fuse various meganucleases and create hybrid enzymes that recognize a new sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Yet others have attempted to alter the DNA interacting aminoacids of the meganuclease to design sequence specific meganucleases in a method named rationally designed meganuclease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Another approach involves using computer models to try to predict as accurately as possible the activity of the modified meganucleases and the specificity of the recognized nucleic sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] A large bank containing several tens of thousands of protein units has been created.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] As opposed to meganucleases, the concept behind ZFNs and TALEN technology is based on a non-specific DNA cutting catalytic domain, which can then be linked to specific DNA sequence recognizing peptides such as zinc fingers and transcription activator-like effectors (TALEs).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The first step to this was to find an endonuclease whose DNA recognition site and cleaving site were separate from each other, a situation that is not the most common among restriction enzymes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Once this enzyme was found, its cleaving portion could be separated which would be very non-specific as it would have no recognition ability.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This portion could then be linked to sequence recognizing peptides that could lead to very high specificity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Zinc finger motifs occur in several transcription factors.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The zinc ion, found in 8% of all human proteins, plays an important role in the organization of their three-dimensional structure.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In transcription factors, it is most often located at the protein-DNA interaction sites, where it stabilizes the motif.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The C-terminal part of each finger is responsible for the specific recognition of the DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The recognized sequences are short, made up of around 3 base pairs, but by combining 6 to 8 zinc fingers whose recognition sites have been characterized, it is possible to obtain specific proteins for sequences of around 20 base pairs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It is therefore possible to control the expression of a specific gene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It has been demonstrated that this strategy can be used to promote a process of angiogenesis in animals.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It is also possible to fuse a protein constructed in this way with the catalytic domain of an endonuclease in order to induce a targeted DNA break, and therefore to use these proteins as genome engineering tools.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The method generally adopted for this involves associating two DNA binding proteins – each containing 3 to 6 specifically chosen zinc fingers – with the catalytic domain of the FokI endonuclease which need to dimerize to cleave the double-strand DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The two proteins recognize two DNA sequences that are a few nucleotides apart.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Linking the two zinc finger proteins to their respective sequences brings the two FokI domains closer together.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] FokI requires dimerization to have nuclease activity and this means the specificity increases dramatically as each nuclease partner would recognize a unique DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] To enhance this effect, FokI nucleases have been engineered that can only function as heterodimers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Several approaches are used to design specific zinc finger nucleases for the chosen sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The most widespread involves combining zinc-finger units with known specificities (modular assembly).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Various selection techniques, using bacteria, yeast or mammal cells have been developed to identify the combinations that offer the best specificity and the best cell tolerance.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The heterodimer functioning nucleases would avoid the possibility of unwanted homodimer activity and thus increase specificity of the DSB.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Although the nuclease portions of both ZFNs and TALEN constructs have similar properties, the difference between these engineered nucleases is in their DNA recognition peptide.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] ZFNs rely on Cys2-His2 zinc fingers and TALEN constructs on TALEs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Both of these DNA recognizing peptide domains have the characteristic that they are naturally found in combinations in their proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Cys2-His2 Zinc fingers typically happen in repeats that are 3 bp apart and are found in diverse combinations in a variety of nucleic acid interacting proteins such as transcription factors.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Each finger of the Zinc finger domain is completely independent and the binding capacity of one finger is impacted by its neighbor.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] TALEs on the other hand are found in repeats with a one-to-one recognition ratio between the amino acids and the recognized nucleotide pairs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Because both zinc fingers and TALEs happen in repeated patterns, different combinations can be tried to create a wide variety of sequence specificities.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Zinc finger nucleases are research and development tools that have already been used to modify a range of genomes, in particular by the laboratories in the Zinc Finger Consortium.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The US company Sangamo BioSciences uses zinc finger nucleases to carry out research into the genetic engineering of stem cells and the modification of immune cells for therapeutic purposes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Modified T lymphocytes are currently undergoing phase I clinical trials to treat a type of brain tumor (glioblastoma) and in the fight against AIDS.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs) are specific DNA-binding proteins that feature an array of 33 or 34-amino acid repeats.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] TALENs are artificial restriction enzymes designed by fusing the DNA cutting domain of a nuclease to TALE domains, which can be tailored to specifically recognize a unique DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] These fusion proteins serve as readily targetable "DNA scissors" for gene editing applications that enable to perform targeted genome modifications such as sequence insertion, deletion, repair and replacement in living cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The nuclease can create double strand breaks at the target site that can be repaired by error-prone non-homologous end-joining (NHEJ), resulting in gene disruptions through the introduction of small insertions or deletions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Each repeat is conserved, with the exception of the so-called repeat variable di-residues (RVDs) at amino acid positions 12 and 13.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The RVDs determine the DNA sequence to which the TALE will bind.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This simple one-to-one correspondence between the TALE repeats and the corresponding DNA sequence makes the process of assembling repeat arrays to recognize novel DNA sequences straightforward.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] These TALEs can be fused to the catalytic domain from a DNA nuclease, FokI, to generate a transcription activator-like effector nuclease (TALEN).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The resultant TALEN constructs combine specificity and activity, effectively generating engineered sequence-specific nucleases that bind and cleave DNA sequences only at pre-selected sites.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The TALEN target recognition system is based on an easy-to-predict code.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] TAL nucleases are specific to their target due in part to the length of their 30+ base pairs binding site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] TALEN can be performed within a 6 base pairs range of any single nucleotide in the entire genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] TALEN constructs are used in a similar way to designed zinc finger nucleases, and have three advantages in targeted mutagenesis: (1) DNA binding specificity is higher, (2) off-target effects are lower, and (3) construction of DNA-binding domains is easier.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] CRISPRs (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) are genetic elements that bacteria use as a kind of acquired immunity to protect against viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] They consist of short sequences that originate from viral genomes and have been incorporated into the bacterial genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Cas (CRISPR associated proteins) process these sequences and cut matching viral DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] By introducing plasmids containing Cas genes and specifically constructed CRISPRs into eukaryotic cells, the eukaryotic genome can be cut at any desired position.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Larger modifications used to be inefficient and error-prone but recent developments allow fairly reliable larger modifications.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] For instance, the quadruple pegRNA strategy (QuadPE) allowed researchers to stably insert large DNA fragments into human cells ranging from 1.6 to 26 kb at an efficiency of about 40%.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] One of the earliest methods of efficiently editing nucleic acids employs nucleobase modifying enzymes directed by nucleic acid guide sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It was first described in the 1990s and has seen a resurgence more recently.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This method has the advantage that it does not require breaking the genomic DNA strands, and thus avoids the random insertions and deletions associated with DNA strand breakage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It is only appropriate for precise editing requiring single nucleotide changes and has found to be highly efficient for this type of editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] ARCUT stands for artificial restriction DNA cutter, it is a technique developed by Makoto Komiyama.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This method uses pseudo-complementary peptide nucleic acid (pcPNA), for identifying cleavage site within the chromosome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Once pcPNA specifies the site, excision is carried out by cerium (CE) and EDTA (chemical mixture), which performs the splicing function.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Meganucleases method of gene editing is the least efficient of the methods mentioned above.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Due to the nature of its DNA-binding element and the cleaving element, it is limited to recognizing one potential target every 1,000 nucleotides.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] ZFN was developed to overcome the limitations of meganuclease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The number of possible targets ZFN can recognise was increased to one in every 140 nucleotides.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] However, both methods are unpredictable because of their DNA-binding elements affecting each other.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] As a result, high degrees of expertise and lengthy and costly validation processes are required.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] TALE nucleases, being the most precise and specific method, yields a higher efficiency than the previous two methods.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It achieves such efficiency because the DNA-binding element consists of an array of TALE subunits, each of them having the capability of recognizing a specific DNA nucleotide chain independently from others, resulting in a higher number of target sites with high precision.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] New TALE nucleases take about one week and a few hundred dollars to create, with specific expertise in molecular biology and protein engineering.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] CRISPR nucleases have a slightly lower precision when compared to the TALE nucleases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This is caused by the need to have a specific nucleotide at one end in order to produce the guide RNA that CRISPR uses to repair the double-strand break it induces.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It has been shown to be the quickest and cheapest method, only costing less than two hundred dollars and a few days of time.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] CRISPR also requires the least amount of expertise in molecular biology, as the design lays in the guide RNA instead of the proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] One major advantage that CRISPR has over the ZFN and TALEN methods is that it can be directed to target different DNA sequences using its ~80nt CRISPR sgRNAs, while both ZFN and TALEN methods required construction and testing of the proteins created for targeting each DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Because off-target activity of an active nuclease would have potentially dangerous consequences at the genetic and organismal levels, the precision of meganucleases, ZFNs, CRISPR, and TALEN-based fusions has been an active area of research.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] While variable figures have been reported, ZFNs tend to have more cytotoxicity than TALEN methods or RNA-guided nucleases, while TALEN and RNA-guided approaches tend to have the greatest efficiency and fewer off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Based on the maximum theoretical distance between DNA binding and nuclease activity, TALEN approaches result in the greatest precision.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The methods for scientists and researchers wanting to study genomic diversity and all possible associated phenotypes were very slow, expensive, and inefficient.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Prior to this new revolution, researchers would have to do single-gene manipulations and tweak the genome one little section at a time, observe the phenotype, and start the process over with a different single-gene manipulation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Therefore, researchers at the Wyss Institute at Harvard University designed the MAGE, a powerful technology that improves the process of in vivo genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It allows for quick and efficient manipulations of a genome, all happening in a machine small enough to put on top of a small kitchen table.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Those mutations combine with the variation that naturally occurs during cell mitosis creating billions of cellular mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Chemically combined, synthetic single-stranded DNA (ssDNA) and a pool of oligonucleotides are introduced at targeted areas of the cell, thereby creating genetic modifications.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The cyclical process involves transformation of ssDNA (by electroporation) followed by outgrowth, during which bacteriophage homologous recombination proteins mediate annealing of ssDNAs to their genomic targets.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Experiments targeting selective phenotypic markers are screened and identified by plating the cells on differential medias.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Each cycle ultimately takes 2.5 hours to process, with additional time required to grow isogenic cultures and characterize mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] By iteratively introducing libraries of mutagenic ssDNAs targeting multiple sites, MAGE can generate combinatorial genetic diversity in a cell population.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] There can be up to 50 genome edits, from single nucleotide base pairs to whole genome or gene networks simultaneously with results in a matter of days.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] MAGE experiments can be divided into three classes, characterized by varying degrees of scale and complexity: (i) many target sites, single genetic mutations; (ii) single target site, many genetic mutations; and (iii) many target sites, many genetic mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] An example of class three was reflected in 2009, where Church and colleagues were able to program *Escherichia coli* to produce five times the normal amount of lycopene, an antioxidant normally found in tomato seeds and linked to anti-cancer properties.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] They applied MAGE to optimize the 1-deoxy-D-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) metabolic pathway in *Escherichia coli* to overproduce isoprenoid lycopene.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It took them about 3 days and just over $1,000 in materials.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The ease, speed, and cost efficiency in which MAGE can alter genomes can transform how industries approach the manufacturing and production of important compounds in the bioengineering, bioenergy, biomedical engineering, synthetic biology, pharmaceutical, agricultural, and chemical industries.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] As of 2012, efficient genome editing had been developed for a wide range of experimental systems ranging from plants to animals, often beyond clinical interest, and was becoming a standard experimental strategy in research labs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The recent generation of rat, zebrafish, maize and tobacco ZFN-mediated mutants and the improvements in TALEN-based approaches testify to the significance of the methods, and the list is expanding rapidly.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Genome editing with engineered nucleases will likely contribute to many fields of life sciences from studying gene functions in plants and animals to gene therapy in humans.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] For instance, the field of synthetic biology which aims to engineer cells and organisms to perform novel functions, is likely to benefit from the ability of engineered nuclease to add or remove genomic elements and therefore create complex systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In addition, gene functions can be studied using stem cells with engineered nucleases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The combination of recent discoveries in genetic engineering, particularly gene editing and the latest improvement in bovine reproduction technologies (e.g.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] *in vitro* embryo culture) allows for genome editing directly in fertilised oocytes using synthetic highly specific endonucleases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Furthermore, gene editing can be applied to certain types of fish in aquaculture such as Atlantic salmon.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Gene editing in fish is currently experimental, but the possibilities include growth, disease resistance, sterility, controlled reproduction, and colour.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Selecting for these traits can allow for a more sustainable environment and better welfare for the fish.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] AquAdvantage salmon is a genetically modified Atlantic salmon developed by AquaBounty Technologies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Thanks to the parallel development of single-cell transcriptomics, genome editing and new stem cell models we are now entering a scientifically exciting period where functional genetics is no longer restricted to animal models but can be performed directly in human samples.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Single-cell gene expression analysis has resolved a transcriptional road-map of human development from which key candidate genes are being identified for functional studies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Using global transcriptomics data to guide experimentation, the CRISPR based genome editing tool has made it feasible to disrupt or remove key genes in order to elucidate function in a human setting.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Genome editing using Meganuclease, ZFNs, and TALEN provides a new strategy for genetic manipulation in plants and are likely to assist in the engineering of desired plant traits by modifying endogenous genes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] For instance, site-specific gene addition in major crop species can be used for 'trait stacking' whereby several desired traits are physically linked to ensure their co-segregation during the breeding processes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Progress in such cases have been recently reported in *Arabidopsis thaliana* and *Zea mays*.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In *Arabidopsis thaliana*, using ZFN-assisted gene targeting, two herbicide-resistant genes (tobacco acetolactate synthase SuRA and SuRB) were introduced to SuR loci with as high as 2% transformed cells with mutations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In Zea mays, disruption of the target locus was achieved by ZFN-induced DSBs and the resulting NHEJ.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] ZFN was also used to drive herbicide-tolerance gene expression cassette (PAT) into the targeted endogenous locus IPK1 in this case.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Such genome modification observed in the regenerated plants has been shown to be inheritable and was transmitted to the next generation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In addition, TALEN-based genome engineering has been extensively tested and optimized for use in plants.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Several optimizations need to be made in order to improve editing plant genomes using ZFN-mediated targeting.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] There is a need for reliable design and subsequent test of the nucleases, the absence of toxicity of the nucleases, the appropriate choice of the plant tissue for targeting, the routes of induction of enzyme activity, the lack of off-target mutagenesis, and a reliable detection of mutated cases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] A common delivery method for CRISPR/Cas9 in plants is *Agrobacterium*-based transformation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] T-DNA is introduced directly into the plant genome by a T4SS mechanism.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Cas9 and gRNA-based expression cassettes are turned into Ti plasmids, which are transformed in *Agrobacterium* for plant application.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] To improve Cas9 delivery in live plants, viruses are being used more effective transgene delivery.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The ideal gene therapy practice is one that replaces the defective gene with a normal allele at its natural location.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This is advantageous over a virally-delivered gene, as there is no need to include the full coding sequences and regulatory sequences when only a small proportion of the gene needs to be altered, as is often the case.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The expression of the partially replaced genes is also more consistent with normal cell biology than full genes that are carried by viral vectors.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The first clinical use of TALEN-based genome editing was in the treatment of CD19+ acute lymphoblastic leukemia in an 11-month old child in 2015.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Modified donor T cells were engineered to attack the leukemia cells, to be resistant to Alemtuzumab, and to evade detection by the host immune system after introduction.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Extensive research has been done in cells and animals using CRISPR-Cas9 to attempt to correct genetic mutations which cause genetic diseases such as Down syndrome, spina bifida, anencephaly, and Turner and Klinefelter syndromes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In February 2019, medical scientists working with Sangamo Therapeutics, headquartered in Richmond, California, announced the first ever "in body" human gene editing therapy to permanently alter DNA - in a patient with Hunter syndrome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Clinical trials by Sangamo involving gene editing using Zinc Finger Nuclease (ZFN) are ongoing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Researchers have used CRISPR-Cas9 gene drives to modify genes associated with sterility in *A. gambiae*, the vector for malaria.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This technique has further implications in eradicating other vector borne diseases such as yellow fever, dengue, and Zika.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The CRISPR-Cas9 system can be programmed to modulate the population of any bacterial species by targeting clinical genotypes or epidemiological isolates.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] It can selectively enable the beneficial bacterial species over the harmful ones by eliminating pathogen, which gives it an advantage over broad-spectrum antibiotics.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Antiviral applications for therapies targeting human viruses such as HIV, herpes, and hepatitis B virus are under research.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] CRISPR can be used to target the virus or the host to disrupt genes encoding the virus cell-surface receptor proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In November 2018, He Jiankui announced that he had edited two human embryos, to attempt to disable the gene for CCR5, which codes for a receptor that HIV uses to enter cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The monkey clones were made in order to study several medical diseases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In the future, an important goal of research into genome editing with engineered nucleases must be the improvement of the safety and specificity of the nucleases action.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] For example, improving the ability to detect off-target events can improve our ability to learn about ways of preventing them.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In addition, zinc-fingers used in ZFNs are seldom completely specific, and some may cause a toxic reaction.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] However, the toxicity has been reported to be reduced by modifications done on the cleavage domain of the ZFN.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In addition, research by Dana Carroll into modifying the genome with engineered nucleases has shown the need for better understanding of the basic recombination and repair machinery of DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In the future, a possible method to identify secondary targets would be to capture broken ends from cells expressing the ZFNs and to sequence the flanking DNA using high-throughput sequencing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Because of the ease of use and cost-efficiency of CRISPR, extensive research is currently being done on it.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] There are now more publications on CRISPR than ZFN and TALEN despite how recent the discovery of CRISPR is.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Both CRISPR and TALEN are favored to be the choices to be implemented in large-scale productions due to their precision and efficiency.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Genome editing occurs also as a natural process without artificial genetic engineering.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The agents that are competent to edit genetic codes are viruses or subviral RNA-agents.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Although DNA has higher efficiency than many other methods in reverse genetics, it is still not highly efficient; in many cases less than half of the treated populations obtain the desired changes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] For example, when one is planning to use the cell's NHEJ to create a mutation, the cell's HDR systems will also be at work correcting the DSB with lower mutational rates.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Traditionally, mice have been the most common choice for researchers as a host of a disease model.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] CRISPR can help bridge the gap between this model and human clinical trials by creating transgenic disease models in larger animals such as pigs, dogs, and non-human primates.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Using the CRISPR-Cas9 system, the programmed Cas9 protein and the sgRNA can be directly introduced into fertilized zygotes to achieve the desired gene modifications when creating transgenic models in rodents.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] This allows bypassing of the usual cell targeting stage in generating transgenic lines, and as a result, it reduces generation time by 90%.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] One potential that CRISPR brings with its effectiveness is the application of xenotransplantation.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In previous research trials, CRISPR demonstrated the ability to target and eliminate endogenous retroviruses, which reduces the risk of transmitting diseases and reduces immune barriers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Eliminating these problems improves donor organ function, which brings this application closer to a reality.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In plants, genome editing is seen as a viable solution to the conservation of biodiversity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Gene drive are a potential tool to alter the reproductive rate of invasive species, although there are significant associated risks.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Many transhumanists see genome editing as a potential tool for human enhancement.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Australian biologist and Professor of Genetics David Andrew Sinclair notes that "the new technologies with genome editing will allow it to be used on individuals (...) to have (...) healthier children" – designer babies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] According to a September 2016 report by the Nuffield Council on Bioethics in the future it may be possible to enhance people with genes from other organisms or wholly synthetic genes to for example improve night vision and sense of smell.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The American National Academy of Sciences and National Academy of Medicine issued a report in February 2017 giving qualified support to human genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In the 2016 *Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community* statement United States Director of National Intelligence, James R.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Clapper, named genome editing as a potential weapon of mass destruction, stating that genome editing conducted by countries with regulatory or ethical standards "different from Western countries" probably increases the risk of the creation of harmful biological agents or products.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] According to the statement the broad distribution, low cost, and accelerated pace of development of this technology, its deliberate or unintentional misuse might lead to far-reaching economic and national security implications.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] For instance, technologies such as CRISPR could be used to make "killer mosquitoes", cause plagues that wipe out staple crops, or create highly deadly viruses.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] According to a September 2016 report by the Nuffield Council on Bioethics, the simplicity and low cost of tools to edit the genetic code will allow amateurs – or "biohackers" – to perform their own experiments, posing a potential risk from the release of genetically modified bugs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] The review also found that the risks and benefits of modifying a person's genome – and having those changes pass on to future generations – are so complex that they demand urgent ethical scrutiny.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Such modifications might have unintended consequences which could harm not only the child, but also their future children, as the altered gene would be in their sperm or eggs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] Furthermore, there are additional concerns about the ecological risks of releasing gene drives into wild populations.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/genome-editing] In 2020, the Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna for "the development of a method for genome editing".
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The RNA editing guide RNA was discovered in 1990 by B.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Simpson through Northern Blot Hybridization in the mitochondrial maxicircle DNA of the eukaryotic parasite Leishmania tarentolae.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Subsequent research throughout the mid-2000s and the following years explored the structure and function of gRNA and the CRISPR-Cas system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] A significant breakthrough occurred in 2012 when it was discovered that gRNA could guide the Cas9 endonuclease to introduce target-specific cuts in double-stranded DNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This discovery led to the 2020 Nobel Prize in Chemistry awarded to Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier for their contributions to the development of CRISPR-Cas9 gene-editing technology.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Trypanosomatid protists and other kinetoplastids have a post-transcriptional RNA modification process known as "RNA editing" that performs a uridine insertion/deletion inside mitochondria.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This mitochondrial DNA is circular and is divided into maxicircles and minicircles.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] A mitochondrion contains about 50 maxicircles which have both coding and non coding regions and consists of approximately 20 kilo bases (kb).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The coding region is highly conserved (16-17kb) and the non-coding region varies depending on the species.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Minicircles are small (around 1 kb) but more numerous than maxicircles, a mitochondrion contains several thousands minicircles.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Maxicircles can encode "cryptogenes" and some gRNAs; minicircles can encode the majority of gRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Some gRNA genes show identical insertion and deletion sites even if they have different sequences, whereas other gRNA sequences are not complementary to pre-edited mRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Maxicircles and minicircles molecules are catenated into a giant network of DNA inside the mitochondrion.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The majority of maxicircle transcripts cannot be translated into proteins due to frameshifts in their sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] These frameshifts are corrected post-transcriptionally through the insertion and deletion of uridine residues at precise sites, which then create an open reading frame.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This open reading frame is subsequently translated into a protein that is homologous to mitochondrial proteins found in other cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The process of uridine insertion and deletion is mediated by short guide RNAs (gRNAs), which encode the editing information through complementary sequences, and allow for base pairing between guanine and uracil (GU) as well as between guanine and cytosine (GC), facilitating the editing process.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Guide RNAs are mainly transcribed from the intergenic region of DNA maxicircle and have sequences complementary to mRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The 3' end of gRNAs contains an oligo 'U' tail (5-24 nucleotides in length) which is in a nonencoded region but interacts and forms a stable complex with A and G rich regions of pre-edited mRNA and gRNA, that are thermodynamically stabilized by a 5' and 3' anchors.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This initial hybrid helps in the recognition of specific mRNA site to be edited.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] RNA editing typically progresses from the 3' to the 5' end on the mRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The initial editing process begins when a gRNA forms an RNA duplex with a complementary mRNA sequence located just downstream of the editing site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This pairing recruits a number of ribonucleoprotein complexes that direct the cleavage of the first mismatched base adjacent to the gRNA-mRNA anchor.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Following this, Uridylyltransferase inserts a 'U' at the 3' end, and RNA ligase then joins the two severed ends.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The process repeats at the next upstream editing site in a similar manner.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] A single gRNA usually encodes the information for several editing sites (an editing "block"), the editing of which produces a complete gRNA/mRNA duplex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This process of sequential editing is known as the enzyme cascade model.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] In the case of "pan-edited" mRNAs, the duplex unwinds and another gRNA forms a duplex with the edited mRNA sequence, initiating another round of editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] These overlapping gRNAs form an editing "domain".
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Some genes contain multiple editing domains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The extent of editing for any particular gene varies among trypanosomatid species.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The variation consists of the loss of editing at the 3' side, probably due to the loss of minicircle sequence classes that encode specific gRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] A retroposition model has been proposed to explain the partial, and in some cases, complete loss of editing through evolution.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Although the loss of editing is typically lethal, such losses have been observed in old laboratory strains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The maintenance of editing over the long evolutionary history of these ancient protists suggests the presence of a selective advantage, the exact nature of which is still uncertain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] It is not clear why trypanosomatids utilize such an elaborate mechanism to produce mRNAs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] It might have originated in the early mitochondria of the ancestor of the kintoplastid protist lineage, since it is present in the bodonids which are ancestral to the trypanosomatids, and may not be present in the euglenoids, which branched from the same common ancestor as the kinetoplastids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] In the protozoan *Leishmania tarentolae*, 12 of the 18 mitochondrial genes are edited using this process.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The mRNA is actually edited twice in succession.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The 3' end is used to anchor the gRNA (gCyb-I gRNA in this case) by basepairing (some G/U pairs are used).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The 5' end does not exactly match and one of three specific endonucleases cleaves the mRNA at the mismatch site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This particular gene has two overlapping gRNA editing sites.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The 5' end of this section is the 3' anchor for another gRNA (gCyb-II gRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Prokaryotes as bacteria and archaea, use CRISPR (clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats) and its associated Cas enzymes, as their adaptive immune system.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] When prokaryotes are infected by phages, and manage to fend off the attack, specific Cas enzymes cut the phage DNA (or RNA) and integrate the fragments into the CRISPR sequence interspaces.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] These stored segments are then recognized during future virus attacks, allowing Cas enzymes to use RNA copies of these segments, along with their associated CRISPR sequences, as gRNA to identify and neutralize the foreign sequences.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Guide RNA targets the complementary sequences by simple Watson-Crick base pairing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] In the type II CRISPR/cas system, the sgRNA directs the Cas-enzyme to target specific regions in the genome for targeted DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The sgRNA is an artificially engineered combination of two RNA molecules: CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA).
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The crRNA component is responsible for binding to the target-specific DNA region, while the tracrRNA component is responsible for the activation of the Cas9 endonuclease activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] These two components are linked by a short tetraloop structure, resulting in the formation of the sgRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The tracrRNA consist of base pairs that form a stem-loop structure, enabling its attachment to the endonuclease enzyme.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The transcription of the CRISPR locus generates crRNA, which contains spacer regions flanked by repeat sequences, typically 18-20 base pairs (bp) in length.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This crRNA guides the Cas9 endonuclease to the complementary target region on the DNA, where it cleaves the DNA, forming what is known as the effector complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Modifications in the crRNA sequence within the sgRNA can alter the binding location, allowing for precise targeting of different DNA regions, effectively making it a programmable system for genome editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The targeting specificity of CRISPR-Cas9 is determined by the 20-nucleotide (nt) sequence at the 5' end of the gRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The desired target sequence must precede the Protospacer Adjacent Motif (PAM), which is a short DNA sequence usually 2-6 base pairs in length that follows the DNA region targeted for cleavage by the CRISPR system, such as CRISPR-Cas9.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The PAM is required for a Cas nuclease to cut and is usually located 3-4 nucleotides downstream from the cut site.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Once the gRNA base pairs with the target, Cas9 induces a double-strand break about 3 nucleotides upstream of the PAM.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The optimal GC content of the guide sequence should be over 50%.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] A higher GC content enhances the stability of the RNA-DNA duplex and reduces off-target hybridization.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The length of guide sequences is typically 20 bp, but they can also range from 17 to 24 bp.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] A longer sequence minimizes off-target effects.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Guide sequences shorter than 17 bp are at risk of targeting multiple loci.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] CRISPR (Clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats)/Cas9 is a technique used for gene editing and gene therapy.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Cas is an endonuclease enzyme that cuts DNA at a specific location directed by a guide RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This is a target-specific technique that can introduce gene knockouts or knock-ins depending on the double strand repair pathway.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Evidence shows that both in vitro and in vivo, tracrRNA is required for Cas9 to bind to the target DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The CRISPR-Cas9 system consists of three main stages.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The first stage involves the extension of bases in the CRISPR locus region by addition of foreign DNA spacers in the genome sequence.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Proteins like cas1 and cas2, assist in finding new spacers.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The next stage involves transcription of CRISPR: pre-crRNA (precursor CRISPR RNA) are expressed by the transcription of CRISPR repeat-spacer array.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Upon further modification, the pre-crRNA is converted to single spacer flanked regions forming short crRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] RNA maturation process is similar in type I and III but different in type II.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The third stage involves binding of cas9 protein and directing it to cleave the DNA segment.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] The Cas9 protein binds to a combined form of crRNA and tracrRNA forming an effector complex.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] This serves as guide RNA for the cas9 protein directing its endonuclease activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] One important method of gene regulation is RNA mutagenesis, which can be introduced through RNA editing with the assistance of gRNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Guide RNA replaces adenosine with inosine at specific target sites, modifying the genetic code.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Adenosine deaminase acts on RNA, bringing post transcriptional modification by altering codons and different protein functions.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Guide RNAs are small nucleolar RNAs that, along with riboproteins, perform intracellular RNA alterations such as ribomethylation in rRNA and the introduction of pseudouridine in preribosomal RNA.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] Guide RNAs bind to the antisense RNA sequence and regulate RNA modification.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/guide-rna] It has been observed that small interfering RNA (siRNA) and micro RNA (miRNA) are generally used as target RNA sequences, and modifications are comparatively easy to introduce due to their small size.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] TAL effectors are proteins that are secreted by *Xanthomonas* bacteria via their type III secretion system when they infect plants.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] The DNA binding domain contains a repeated highly conserved 33–34 amino acid sequence with divergent 12th and 13th amino acids.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] These two positions, referred to as the Repeat Variable Diresidue (RVD), are highly variable and show a strong correlation with specific nucleotide recognition.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] This straightforward relationship between amino acid sequence and DNA recognition has allowed for the engineering of specific DNA-binding domains by selecting a combination of repeat segments containing the appropriate RVDs.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Notably, slight changes in the RVD and the incorporation of "nonconventional" RVD sequences can improve targeting specificity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] The non-specific DNA cleavage domain from the end of the FokI endonuclease can be used to construct hybrid nucleases that are active in a yeast assay.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] These reagents are also active in plant cells and in animal cells.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Initial TALEN studies used the wild-type FokI cleavage domain, but some subsequent TALEN studies also used FokI cleavage domain variants with mutations designed to improve cleavage specificity and cleavage activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] The FokI domain functions as a dimer, requiring two constructs with unique DNA binding domains for sites in the target genome with proper orientation and spacing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Both the number of amino acid residues between the TALE DNA binding domain and the FokI cleavage domain and the number of bases between the two individual TALEN binding sites appear to be important parameters for achieving high levels of activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] The simple relationship between amino acid sequence and DNA recognition of the TALE binding domain allows for the efficient engineering of proteins.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] In this case, artificial gene synthesis is problematic because of improper annealing of the repetitive sequence found in the TALE binding domain.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] One solution to this is to use a publicly available software program (DNAWorks) to calculate oligonucleotides suitable for assembly in a two step PCR oligonucleotide assembly followed by whole gene amplification.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] A number of modular assembly schemes for generating engineered TALE constructs have also been reported.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Both methods offer a systematic approach to engineering DNA binding domains that is conceptually similar to the modular assembly method for generating zinc finger DNA recognition domains.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Once the TALEN constructs have been assembled, they are inserted into plasmids; the target cells are then transfected with the plasmids, and the gene products are expressed and enter the nucleus to access the genome.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Alternatively, TALEN constructs can be delivered to the cells as mRNAs, which removes the possibility of genomic integration of the TALEN-expressing protein.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Using an mRNA vector can also dramatically increase the level of homology directed repair (HDR) and the success of introgression during gene editing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] TALEN can be used to edit genomes by inducing double-strand breaks (DSB), which cells respond to with repair mechanisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) directly ligates DNA from either side of a double-strand break where there is very little or no sequence overlap for annealing.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] This repair mechanism induces errors in the genome via indels (insertion or deletion), or chromosomal rearrangement; any such errors may render the gene products coded at that location non-functional.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Because this activity can vary depending on the species, cell type, target gene, and nuclease used, it should be monitored when designing new systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] A simple heteroduplex cleavage assay can be run which detects any difference between two alleles amplified by PCR.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Cleavage products can be visualized on simple agarose gels or slab gel systems.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Alternatively, DNA can be introduced into a genome through NHEJ in the presence of exogenous double-stranded DNA fragments.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Homology directed repair can also introduce foreign DNA at the DSB as the transfected double-stranded sequences are used as templates for the repair enzymes.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] TALEN has been used to efficiently modify plant genomes, creating economically important food crops with favorable nutritional qualities.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] They have also been harnessed to develop tools for the production of biofuels.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] In addition, it has been used to engineer stably modified human embryonic stem cell and induced pluripotent stem cell (IPSCs) clones and human erythroid cell lines, to generate knockout *C. elegans*, knockout rats, knockout mice, and knockout zebrafish.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Moreover, the method can be used to generate knockin organisms.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Wu et al.obtained a Sp110 knockin cattle using Talen nickases to induce increased resistance of tuberculosis.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] This approach has also been used to generate knockin rats by TALEN mRNA microinjection in one-cell embryos.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] TALEN has also been utilized experimentally to correct the genetic errors that underlie disease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] For example, it has been used *in vitro* to correct the genetic defects that cause disorders such as sickle cell disease, xeroderma pigmentosum, and epidermolysis bullosa.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Recently, it was shown that TALEN can be used as tools to harness the immune system to fight cancers; TALEN-mediated targeting can generate T cells that are resistant to chemotherapeutic drugs and show anti-tumor activity.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] In theory, the genome-wide specificity of engineered TALEN fusions allows for correction of errors at individual genetic loci via homology-directed repair from a correct exogenous template.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] In reality, however, the *in situ* application of TALEN is currently limited by the lack of an efficient delivery mechanism, unknown immunogenic factors, and uncertainty in the specificity of TALEN binding.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Another emerging application of TALEN is its ability to combine with other genome engineering tools, such as meganucleases.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] The DNA binding region of a TAL effector can be combined with the cleavage domain of a meganuclease to create a hybrid architecture combining the ease of engineering and highly specific DNA binding activity of a TAL effector with the low site frequency and specificity of a meganuclease.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] In comparison to other genome editing techniques, TALEN falls in the middle in terms of difficulty and cost.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Unlike ZFNs, TALEN recognizes single nucleotides.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] It's far more straightforward to engineer interactions between TALEN DNA binding domains and their target nucleotides than it is to create interactions with ZFNs and their target nucleotide triplets.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] The off-target activity of an active nuclease may lead to unwanted double-strand breaks and may consequently yield chromosomal rearrangements and/or cell death.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Studies have been carried out to compare the relative nuclease-associated toxicity of available technologies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/talen] Based on these studies and the maximal theoretical distance between DNA binding and nuclease activity, TALEN constructs are believed to have the greatest precision of the currently available technologies.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/zinc-finger-nuclease] It was initially created by researcher Srinivasan Chandrasegaran.
[src:crispr-gene-editing/zinc-finger-nuclease] The DNA-binding domains of individual ZFNs typically contain between three and six individual zinc finger repeats and can each recognize between 9 and 18 basepairs.
